'''Palmyra''' {{IPAc-en|<U+02CC>|p|<U+00E6>|l|<U+02C8>|m|a<U+026A>r|<U+0259>}}, ({{lang-arc|<U+072C><U+0715><U+0721><U+0718><U+072A><U+072C><U+0710>}}; {{lang-ar|<U+062A><U+062F><U+0645><U+0631>}}; {{lang-he|<U+05EA><U+05B7><U+05BC><U+05D3><U+05B0><U+05DE><U+05D5><U+05B9><U+05E8>}}; {{lang-grc|<U+03A0><U+03B1><U+03BB><U+03BC><U+03CD><U+03C1><U+03B1>}}), was an ancient [[Semitic people|Semitic]] city, located in [[Homs Governorate]], [[Syria]]. Dating back to the [[Neolithic]], Palmyra was first attested in the early second millennium BC, as a caravan stop for travelers crossing the [[Syrian Desert]]. The city is mentioned in the [[Hebrew Bible]] and in the annals of the [[List of Assyrian kings|Assyrian kings]], then it was incorporated into the [[Seleucid Empire]], followed by the [[Roman Empire]] which brought great prosperity.

Palmyra's wealth allowed the construction of many monumental projects. By the third century, Palmyra was turned into a prosperous metropolis, with a strong army capable of defeating the [[Sasanian Empire|Sassanid empire]] in 260. Following the victory, Palmyra's chief [[Odaenathus]] was proclaimed king but was assassinated in 267. He was succeeded by his minor son, under the regency of queen [[Zenobia]], who started invading the Roman eastern provinces in 269. The rebellion was masked by a nominal subordination to Rome. However, the situation escalated and the Palmyrene rulers adopted the imperial titles in 271. Roman emperor Aurelian defeated Palmyra in 272, and destroyed it in 273 after a failed second rebellion. Palmyra became a minor city under the rule of the [[Byzantine Empire|Byzantines]], [[Rashidun Caliphate|Rashiduns]], [[Ummayads]], [[Abbassids]], [[Mamluk Sultanate (Cairo)|Mamluks]], and their vassals. After being destroyed by the [[Timurids]] in 1400, Palmyra remained a small village under the rule of the [[Ottomans]] until 1918, then the [[Arab Kingdom of Syria|Syrian kingdom]], followed by the [[French Mandate for Syria and the Lebanon|French mandate]]. In 1929 the French started evacuating the villagers into the newly built village of [[Tadmur]]. The evacuation was completed in 1932 and the site became abandoned and available for excavations.

The Palmyrenes were mainly a mix of [[Amorites]], [[Arameans]] and [[Arabs]],<ref name="arab palm">{{cite book|url=https://books.google.nl/books?id=41-MAgAAQBAJ&pg=PA280#v=onepage&q&f=false|title=Ancient Syria: A Three Thousand Year History|author=Trevor Bryce|page= 280|year= 2014}}</ref> in addition to a [[Jews|Jewish]] minority. The society was tribal and the inhabitants spoke their own [[Palmyrene dialect|dialect]] of [[Aramaic language|Aramaic]], in addition to [[Greek language|Greek]]. Both of the languages were replaced by [[Arabic language|Arabic]] following the Arab conquest in 634. Palmyra's [[Culture of Syria|local]] culture was influenced by the [[Greco-Roman_world#Greco-Roman_Culture|Greco-Roman]] and [[Culture of Iran|Persian]] cultures, which produced a distinctive art and architecture. The city's inhabitants worshiped [[Canaanite religion|local deities]], in addition to [[Ancient Mesopotamian religion|Mesopotamian]] and [[Arabian mythology|Arab]] gods. They later converted to [[Christianity]] in the fourth century, followed by [[Islam]] in the second half of the first millennium.

The Palmyrene political organization was based on the Greek city-state model. It was governed by a senate responsible for both the public works and the military. After gaining the status of a [[Colonia (Roman)|Colonia]] in the third century, Palmyra's incorporated Roman institutions to its system before adopting a monarchical system in 260. Palmyra gained its wealth from caravan trade. The Palmyrenes were renowned merchants who established colonies along the [[Silk Road]], and conducted their operations all around the Roman empire.

==Location and etymology==
Palmyra is located {{convert|215|km|abbr=on}} to the northeast of the Syrian capital [[Damascus]],<ref name="chus">{{cite web |url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/2/hi/middle_east/7729718.stm |title= Syria uncovers 'largest church' |publisher= BBC News |date= 2008|accessdate= 8 February 2015}}</ref> in an [[oasis]],<ref>{{cite book|url=https://books.google.nl/books?id=8kLFfE1qPhIC&pg=PA56#v=onepage&q&f=false|title= Palmyra and Its Empire: Zenobia's Revolt Against Rome|author= Richard Stoneman|page= 56|year= 1994}}</ref> surrounded by [[Date palm|palms]] of which twenty varieties were reported.<ref name="yoel2">{{cite book|url=https://books.google.nl/books?id=x1l_MfEV6kkC&pg=PA235#v=onepage&q&f=false|title= A Linguistic Happening in Memory of Ben Schwartz: Studies in Anatolian, Italic, and Other Indo-European Languages|author= Yo<U+00EB>l L. Arbeitman|page= 235|year= 1988}}</ref> A small [[Wadi]] named [[al-Qubur]], crosses the area,<ref>{{cite book|url=https://books.google.nl/books?id=YnUMAQAAMAAJ&q|title= Annales arch<U+00E9>ologiques Arabes Syriennes, Volume 42|language= ar|author= Direction g<U+00E9>n<U+00E9>rale des antiquit<U+00E9>s et des mus<U+00E9>es, R<U+00E9>publique arabe syrienne|page= 246|year=1996}}</ref> it flows from the hills in the west and passes the city, before disappearing in the eastern gardens of the oasis.<ref name="icaan4">{{cite book|url=https://books.google.nl/books?id=FgML1EdUiWUC&pg=PA229#v=onepage&q&f=false|title= Proceedings of the 4th International Congress of the Archaeology of the Ancient Near East, 29 March - 3 April 2004, Freie Universit<U+00E4>t Berlin: The reconstruction of environment : natural resources and human interrelations through time ; art history : visual communication|author= Hartmut K<U+00FC>hne, Rainer Maria Czichon, Florian Janoscha Kreppner|page= 229|year= 2008}}</ref> To the south of the Wadi, a spring named [[Efqa]] is located.<ref name="PALM1">{{cite book|url=https://books.google.nl/books?id=_LfXg2r6FT0C&pg=PA17#v=onepage&q&f=false|title= The Palmyrenes of Dura-Europos: A Study of Religious Interaction in Roman Syria|author=  Lucinda Dirven|page= 17|year= 1999}}</ref> [[Pliny the Elder]] described the town in the 70s AD,{{#tag:ref|Pliny mentioned that Palmyra was independent, but by 70 AD, Palmyra was part of the Roman empire and Pliny's account over Palmyra's political situation is dismissed by modern scholars, as it is considered to rely on older accounts, dating to the period of [[Octavian]], when Palmyra was independent.<ref>{{cite book|url=https://books.google.nl/books?id=_UR8AgAAQBAJ&pg=PT73#v=onepage&q&f=false|title= Between Rome and Persia: The Middle Euphrates, Mesopotamia and Palmyra under Roman control|author= Peter Edwell|page= 73|year= 2007}}</ref>|group=note}} as famous for its location, the richness of its soil,<ref name="pliny">{{cite book|url=https://books.google.nl/books?id=E5yCAgAAQBAJ&pg=PA124#v=onepage&q&f=false|title= Rome's Eastern Trade: International Commerce and Imperial Policy 31 BC - AD 305|author= Gary K. Young|page= 124|year= 2003}}</ref> and the water springs that surrounded it, making the agricultural and herding activities possible.<ref name="pliny" />

''Tadmor'' is the [[Semitic languages|Semitic]] and earliest attested native name of the city, it appeared in the first half of the second millennium BC.<ref name="yoel">{{cite book|url=https://books.google.nl/books?id=x1l_MfEV6kkC&pg=PA238#v=onepage&q&f=false|title= A Linguistic Happening in Memory of Ben Schwartz: Studies in Anatolian, Italic, and Other Indo-European Languages|author= Yo<U+00EB>l L. Arbeitman|page= 238|year= 1988}}</ref> The etymology of ''Tadmor'' is vague, [[Albert Schultens]] considered it to be derived from the Semitic word for [[Date palm#Dates|dates]] (''Tamar''),{{#tag:ref|The Semitic word T.M.R is the common root for the words that designate palm dates in [[Arabic language|Arabic]], [[Hebrew language|Hebrew]], [[Ge'ez language|Ge'ez]] and other Semitic languages.<ref>{{cite book|url=https://books.google.nl/books?id=t_9NkGsNtcYC&pg=PA445#v=onepage&q&f=false|title= Hebrew in Its West Semitic Setting: A Comparative Survey of Non-Masoretic Hebrew Dialects and Traditions, Deel 1|author= A. Murtonen|page= 445|year= 1989}}</ref>|group=note}}<ref name="charnok">{{cite book|url=https://books.google.nl/books?id=I2BulY4WvsYC&pg=PA200#v=onepage&q&f=false|title= Local Etymology: A Derivative Dictionary of Geographical Names|author= Richard Stephen Charnock|page= 200|year= 1859}}</ref> in reference to the Palm trees that surround the city.{{#tag:ref|The [[Hebrew Bible]] mentions ''Tadmor'' as a city built by [[Solomon]], Schultens' argued that it is written ''Tamor'', and in the margin ''Tadmor''.<ref name="charnok" /> Schultens considered ''Tamor'' to be derived from ''Tamar'',<ref name="charnok" /> however, the inclusion of a -''d''- in ''Tamar'' can not be explained.<ref name="yoel2" />|group=note}}<ref name="yoel2" /> The name ''Palmyra'' appeared during the early first century AD,<ref name="yoel" /> in the works of Pliny the Elder,<ref name="yoe3">{{cite book|url=https://books.google.nl/books?id=x1l_MfEV6kkC&pg=PA248#v=onepage&q&f=false|title= A Linguistic Happening in Memory of Ben Schwartz: Studies in Anatolian, Italic, and Other Indo-European Languages|author= Yo<U+00EB>l L. Arbeitman|page= 248|year= 1988}}</ref> and was used throughout the [[Greco-Roman]] world.<ref name="charnok" /> The general view holds that ''Palmyra'' is derived from ''Tadmor'' either as an alteration, which was supported by Schultens,{{#tag:ref|According to Schultens, the [[Ancient Rome|Romans]] altered the name from ''Tadmor'' to ''Talmura'', and afterward to ''Palmura'' (from the [[Latin language|Latin]] word ''palma'', meaning [[Arecaceae|palm]]),<ref name="yoel" /> in reference to the palm trees. Then the name reached its final form ''Palmyra''.<ref>{{cite book|url=https://books.google.nl/books?id=I2BulY4WvsYC&pg=PA201#v=onepage&q&f=false|title= Local Etymology: A Derivative Dictionary of Geographical Names|author= Richard Stephen Charnock|page= 201|year= 1859}}</ref> |group=note}}<ref name="charnok" /> or as a translation using the [[Greek language|Greek]] word for palm (''Palame''),{{#tag:ref|The name could be a translation of ''Tadmor'' (assuming that it meant palm), and derived from the [[Greek language|Greek]] word (Palame).<ref name="yoel2" />|group=note}}<ref name="yoel2" /> which is supported by [[Jean Starcky]].<ref name="yoel" />

[[Michael Patrick O'Connor]] argued for a [[Hurrian language|Hurrian]] origin of both ''Palmyra'' and ''Tadmor'',<ref name="yoel" /> citing the incapability of explaining the alterations to the theorized roots of both names, which are represented in the adding of a ''-d-'' to ''Tamar'' and a ''-ra-'' to ''palame''.<ref name="yoel2" /> According to this theory, '' Tadmor'' is derived from the Hurrian word ''Tad'', meaning ''to love'', + a [[mid vowel]] rising (mVr) [[formant]] ''Mar''. ''Palmyra'' is derived from the word ''Pal'', meaning ''to know'', + the same mVr formant ''Mar''.<ref>{{cite book|url=https://books.google.nl/books?id=x1l_MfEV6kkC&pg=PA236#v=onepage&q&f=false|title= A Linguistic Happening in Memory of Ben Schwartz: Studies in Anatolian, Italic, and Other Indo-European Languages|author= Yo<U+00EB>l L. Arbeitman|page= 236|year= 1988}}</ref>

== History ==
[[File:Efqa.png|thumb|Efqa spring (dried up in 1994).<ref>{{cite book|url=https://books.google.nl/books?id=DqMrR29Cc7MC&pg=PA18#v=onepage&q&f=false|title= Empress Zenobia: Palmyra s Rebel Queen|author=Pat Southern|page= 18|year= 2008}}</ref>]]
The site of Palmyra provided evidence for a [[neolithic]] settlement near Efqa,<ref name="salk">{{cite book|url=https://books.google.nl/books?id=R44VRnNCzAYC&pg=PA565#v=onepage&q&f=false|title= International Dictionary of Historic Places: Middle East and Africa, Volume 4|author=Trudy Ring,Robert M. Salkin,Sharon La Boda|page= 565|year= 1996}}</ref> with [[Stone tool#Neolithic industries|stone tools]] discovered and dated to 7500 BC.<ref name="esth">{{cite book|url=https://books.google.nl/books?id=AIgdBAAAQBAJ&pg=PA566#v=onepage&q&f=false|title= The Oxford Companion to Classical Civilization|author=Simon Hornblower, Antony Spawforth, Esther Eidinow|page= 566|year= 2014}}</ref> The use of [[archaeoacoustics]] in the [[Tell]] beneath the [[Temple of Bel]] revealed traces of a cultic activity dated to 2300 BC.<ref>{{cite book|url=https://books.google.nl/books?id=HU5mAAAAMAAJ&q|title= Space archaeology|author=Shiruku R<U+014D>do-gaku Kenky<U+016B> Sent<U+0101>|page= 19|year= 1995}}</ref><ref>{{cite book|url=https://books.google.nl/books?id=z8XpAAAAMAAJ&q|title= The Art of Palmyra|author=Malcolm A. R. Colledge|page= 11|year= 1976}}</ref><ref name="stan">{{cite book|url=https://books.google.nl/books?id=3SapTk5iGDkC&pg=PA293#v=onepage&q&f=false|title= Cities of the Middle East and North Africa: A Historical Encyclopedia|author=Michael Dumper,Bruce E. Stanley|page= 293|year= 2007}}</ref> 

===Early period===
Palmyra entered the historic records in c. 2000 BC, when a certain ''Puzur-Ishtar the Tadmorean'' made a contract at an [[Assyria#Dynasty of Puzur-Ashur I.2C 2025.E2.80.931809 BC.2C Old Assyrian Empire|Assyrian]] trading colony in [[Kultepe]].<ref name="esth" /><ref>{{cite book|url=https://books.google.nl/books?ei=oeW1VOS2MoTqOIyYgeAH&hl=nl&id=zys8AAAAMAAJ&dq|title= The Journal of Roman Studies, Volumes 40-42|author=Society for the Promotion of Roman Studies|page= 1|year= 1998}}</ref> Palmyra was next mentioned in the [[Mari, Syria#Mari tablets|Tablets of Mari]] as a station for trade caravans, and the halting place for many nomadic tribes such as the [[Suteans]].<ref name="palm3">{{cite book|url=https://books.google.nl/books?id=_LfXg2r6FT0C&pg=PA18#v=onepage&q&f=false|title= The Palmyrenes of Dura-Europos: A Study of Religious Interaction in Roman Syria|author= Lucinda Dirven|page= 18|year= 1999}}</ref> King [[Shamshi-Adad I]] of Assyria passed the area on his way to the [[Mediterranean Sea|Mediterranean]], at the beginning of the 18th century BC.<ref>{{cite book|url=https://books.google.nl/books?id=0d1JAgAAQBAJ&pg=PA234#v=onepage&q&f=false|title= The Ancient Near East: History, Society and Economy|author=Mario Liverani|page= 234|year= 2013}}</ref> By then, Palmyra was the kingdom of [[Qatna]]'s most eastern point.<ref>{{cite book|url=https://books.google.nl/books?id=2-4uAQAAIAAJ&q|title= al-Jaz<U+012B>rah al-S<U+016B>r<U+012B>yah, al-tur<U+0101>th al-<U+1E25>a<U+1E0D><U+0101>r<U+012B> wa-al-<U+1E63>il<U+0101>t al-mutab<U+0101>dalah: waq<U+0101><U+02BC>i<U+02BB> al-mu<U+02BC>tamar al-duwal<U+012B>, Dayr al-Z<U+016B>r 22-25 N<U+012B>s<U+0101>n 1996|author= Michelle Makdesi, Ma'mun Abd al-Karim |page= 325|year= 2002}}</ref> The town was mentioned in a tablet discovered at [[Emar]] dated to the 13th century BC, and records the names of two ''Tadmorean'' witnesses.<ref name="palm3" /> At the beginning of the 11th century BC, king [[Tiglath-Pileser I]] of Assyria recorded in his annals the defeat he inflicted upon the ''[[Arameans]]'' of ''Tadmar''.<ref name="palm3" />

The [[Hebrew Bible]] ([[Books of Chronicles|Second Book of Chronicles]] 8:4) records ''Tadmor'' as a desert city built or fortified by King [[Solomon]] of [[Kingdom of Israel (united monarchy)|Israel]],<ref>{{cite book|url=https://books.google.nl/books?id=h17MWNlkEcwC&pg=PA175#v=onepage&q&f=false|title= The Penny Cyclopaedia of the Society for the Difussion of Useful Knowledge, Volume 17|author=Charles Knight|page= 175|year= 1840}}</ref> it is likewise mentioned in [[Talmud]] ([[Yebamot]] 17a-b).<ref>{{cite book|url=https://books.google.nl/books?id=ZVJTAAAAYAAJ&q|title= Hebrew-English Edition of the Babylonian Talmud: Yebamoth|author=Isidore Epstein|page= 194|year= 1984}}</ref> [[Flavius Josephus]]' mention the Greek name ''Palmyra'' and also attribute the founding of ''Tadmor'' to Solomon in his ''[[Antiquities of the Jews]]'' (Book VIII).<ref>{{cite book|url=https://books.google.nl/books?id=IA-YlZqHv90C&pg=PA320#v=onepage&q&f=false|title= The Roman Near East, 31 B.C.-A.D. 337|author= Fergus Millar|page= 320|year= 1993}}</ref> Later [[Islamic]] traditions attributes the founding of the city to the [[Jinn#Solomon and the Jinn|Jinn]] of Solomon.<ref>{{cite book|url=https://books.google.nl/books?id=91YymsCw5DIC&pg=PA389#v=onepage&q&f=false|title= History of Syria, Including Lebanon and Palestine|author= Phillip K. Hitti|page= 389|year= 2004}}</ref> The association of Palmyra with Solomon could be a confusion between Palmyra (''Tadmor''), and a city built by Solomon in the land of [[Judea]], mentioned in the [[Books of Kings]] (9:18) as ''Tamar''.<ref name="trev">{{cite book|url=https://books.google.nl/books?id=Xno9AgAAQBAJ&pg=PA276#v=onepage&q&f=false|title= Ancient Syria: A Three Thousand Year History|author= Trevor Bryce|page= 276|year= 2014}}</ref> The description of ''Tadmor'' and its buildings in the Bible, does not fit the known archaeological findings of Palmyra, which was a mere settlement during the days of Solomon in the 10th century BC.<ref name="trev" />

===Hellenistic and Roman periods===
[[File:Temple of Baal-Shamin, Palmyra.jpg|thumb|left|Temple of Baalshamin.]]
[[File:Center of Bel.jpg|thumb|left|Temple of Bel, the main shrine.]]

The [[Hellenistic period]] under the [[Seleucids]] saw Palmyra turning into a prosperous settlement,<ref name="trev" /> that owed allegiance to the Seleucid monarch.<ref>{{cite book|url=https://books.google.nl/books?id=8kLFfE1qPhIC&pg=PA52#v=onepage&q&f=false|title= Palmyra and Its Empire: Zenobia's Revolt Against Rome|author=  Richard Stoneman|page= 52|year= 1994}}</ref> In 217 BC, a Palmyrene force led by a [[Sheikh]] named [[Zabdibel]],{{#tag:ref|Zabdibel is not explicitly identified as a Palmyrene, however, this name is only attested in Palmyra.<ref>{{cite book|url=https://books.google.nl/books?id=Xno9AgAAQBAJ&pg=PA359#v=onepage&q&f=false|title= Ancient Syria: A Three Thousand Year History|author=  Trevor Bryce|page= 359|year= 2014}}</ref>|group=note}} joined the army of king [[Antiochus III]] in the [[Battle of Raphia]].<ref name="trev34">{{cite book|url=https://books.google.nl/books?id=Xno9AgAAQBAJ&pg=PA278#v=onepage&q&f=false|title= Ancient Syria: A Three Thousand Year History|author=  Trevor Bryce|page= 278|year= 2014}}</ref> Toward the middle of the Hellenistic era, Palmyra, formerly restricted in the south of al-Qubur's wadi, started to expand beyond the northern bank.<ref name="trev34sssssss">{{cite book|url=https://books.google.nl/books?id=FgML1EdUiWUC&pg=PA231#v=onepage&q&f=false|title= Proceedings of the 4th International Congress of the Archaeology of the Ancient Near East, 29 March - 3 April 2004, Freie Universit<U+00E4>t Berlin: The reconstruction of environment : natural resources and human interrelations through time ; art history : visual communication|author= Hartmut K<U+00FC>hne, Rainer Maria Czichon, Florian Janoscha Kreppner|page= 231|year= 2008}}</ref> By the late second century BC, the tower tombs in the Palmyrene Valley of Tombs began to be constructed,<ref name="trev34" /> in addition to the city temples, most importantly the temples of [[Baalshamin]], [[Al-l<U+0101>t]] and the Hellenistic temple.<ref name="trev" /><ref name="trev34s">{{cite book|url=https://books.google.nl/books?id=h5cMho6zFckC&pg=PA63#v=onepage&q&f=false|title= Roman Palmyra: Identity, Community, and State Formation|author= Andrew M. Smith II|page= 63|year= 2013}}</ref> 

In 64 BC, the [[Roman Republic]] annexed the Seleucid kingdom, and the Roman general [[Pompey]] established the [[Syria (Roman province)|province of Syria]], but Palmyra was left independent,<ref name="trev34" /> trading with both Rome and [[Parthian empire|Parthia]] but belonging to neither.<ref name="elto">{{cite book|url=https://books.google.nl/books?id=N0jAQ1oP3_wC&pg=PA90#v=onepage&q&f=false|title= Frontiers of the Roman Empire|author= Hugh Elton|page= 90|year= 2013}}</ref> The earliest known Palmyrene inscription is dated to c. 44 BC,<ref name="dirvas">{{cite book|url=https://books.google.nl/books?id=_LfXg2r6FT0C&pg=PA19#v=onepage&q&f=false|title= The Palmyrenes of Dura-Europos: A Study of Religious Interaction in Roman Syria|author= Lucinda Dirven|page= 19|year= 1999}}</ref> and by then, Palmyra was still a minor [[Sheikhdom]], offering water to caravans that occasionally took the desert route, along which Palmyra was situated.<ref name="warwik">{{cite book|url=https://books.google.nl/books?id=qQKIAgAAQBAJ&pg=PA74#v=onepage&q&f=false|title= Rome in the East: The Transformation of an Empire|author= Warwick Ball|page= 74|year= 2002}}</ref> However, according to [[Appian]], Palmyra was wealthy enough for [[Mark Antony]] to send a force aimed at conquering it in 41 BC.<ref name="elto" /> The Palmyrenes evacuated and headed into Parthia's lands beyond the [[Euphrates]] eastern bank,<ref name="elto" /> which they prepared to be defended.<ref name="dirvas" />
[[File:Lion in the garden of Palmyra Archeological Museum, 2010-04-21.jpg|thumb|The lion of Al-l<U+0101>t (first century AD), stood at the entrance of Bel's temple.]]
Palmyra became part of the [[Roman Empire]] when it paid tribute in the early years of emperor [[Tiberius]]' reign c. 14 AD.<ref name="trev34" /> The Roman imperial period brought a great prosperity to Palmyra, which enjoyed a privileged status under the empire and retained much of its internal autonomy.<ref name="trev34" /> The Romans defined the boundaries of Palmyra's region, a boundary marker established by Roman governor [[Quintus Caecilius Metellus Creticus Silanus|Silanus]] was found 75 kilometers to the northwest of Palmyra at [[Khirbet el-Bilaas]].<ref>{{cite book|url=https://books.google.nl/books?id=_UR8AgAAQBAJ&pg=PT70&lpg#v=onepage&q&f=false|title= Between Rome and Persia: The Middle Euphrates, Mesopotamia and Palmyra under Roman control|author= Peter Edwell|page= 70|year= 2007}}</ref> Another marker that defined Palmyra's southwestern borders was found at [[Qasr al-Hayr al-Gharbi]],<ref name="trevo 40">{{cite book|url=https://books.google.nl/books?id=Xno9AgAAQBAJ&pg=PA284#v=onepage&q&f=false|title= Ancient Syria: A Three Thousand Year History|author= Trevor Bryce|page= 284|year= 2014}}</ref> while the borders in the east extended to the Euphrates valley.<ref name="trevo 40" /> 

The earliest Palmyrene text that attests the Roman existence in the city is dated to 18 AD, when the Roman general [[Germanicus]] sought to establish a friendly relation with Parthia, and sent a Palmyrene named ''Alexandros'' to [[Characene|Mesene]], a Parthian vassal kingdom.{{#tag:ref|No evidence for Germanicus visiting Palmyra exist.<ref>{{cite book|url=https://books.google.nl/books?id=h5cMho6zFckC&pg=PA24#v=onepage&q&f=false|title= Roman Palmyra: Identity, Community, and State Formation|author= Andrew M. Smith II|page= 24|year= 2013}}</ref>|group=note}}<ref name="palmoi">{{cite book|url=https://books.google.nl/books?id=_LfXg2r6FT0C&pg=PA20#v=onepage&q&f=false|title= The Palmyrenes of Dura-Europos: A Study of Religious Interaction in Roman Syria|author= Lucinda Dirven|page= 20|year= 1999}}</ref> This was followed in 19 AD, by the arrival of [[Legio X Fretensis]].{{#tag:ref|The legion was part of Germanicus' eastern campaign and was not stationed in the city as a garrison.<ref>{{cite book|url=https://books.google.nl/books?id=yH4MQy0wrbcC&pg=PA12#v=onepage&q&f=false|title=Legio X Fretensis|author= Edward D<U+0105>browa|page= 12|year= 1993}}</ref>|group=note}}<ref name="hildo">{{cite book|url=https://books.google.nl/books?id=Ig0_4HeMh-AC&pg=PA769#v=onepage&q&f=false|title= Politische Geschichte: (Provinzien und Randv<U+00F6>lker: Mesopotamien, Armenien, Iran, S<U+00FC>darabien, Rom und der Ferne Osten), Deel 2,Volume 9|author= Hildegard Temporini|page= 769|year= 1978}}</ref> The Roman authority was minimal during the first century, they had tax collectors in the city,<ref name="elroo">{{cite book|url=https://books.google.nl/books?id=N0jAQ1oP3_wC&pg=PA91#v=onepage&q&f=false|title= Frontiers of the Roman Empire|author= Hugh Elton|page= 91|year= 2013}}</ref> and built a road that connected Palmyra with [[Sura, Syria|Sura]] in 75 AD.{{#tag:ref|Commissioned by [[Marcus Ulpius Traianus (senior)|Traianus]].<ref name="elroo3">{{cite book|url=https://books.google.nl/books?id=N0jAQ1oP3_wC&pg=PA92#v=onepage&q&f=false|title= Frontiers of the Roman Empire|author= Hugh Elton|page= 92|year= 2013}}</ref>|group=note}}<ref name="elroo3" /> The Romans also made use of Palmyrene soldiers,<ref name="dadas">{{cite book|url=https://books.google.nl/books?id=ecfiAAAAQBAJ&pg=PA25#v=onepage&q&f=false|title=Empress Zenobia: Palmyra's Rebel Queen|author= Pat Southern|page= 25|year= 2008}}</ref> however, no local [[Roman magistrate|magistrates]] or [[Prefect#Ancient Rome|prefects]] are recorded in the city as it was the case for typical Roman cities.<ref name="elroo3" /> Palmyra witnessed an intense construction movement during the first century, which included the city's first walled fortifications,<ref name="hildo" /> and the [[Temple of Bel]], which was finished and dedicated in 32 AD.<ref>{{cite book|url=https://books.google.nl/books?id=IA-YlZqHv90C&pg=PA323#v=onepage&q&f=false|title= The Roman Near East, 31 B.C.-A.D. 337|author= Fergus Millar|page= 323|year= 1993}}</ref> The first century saw Palmyra's transformation from a minor desert station for caravans into a leading trading center,{{#tag:ref|The transformation already began in the first century BC.<ref name="elrood">{{cite book|url=https://books.google.nl/books?id=_UR8AgAAQBAJ&pg=PT64#v=onepage&q&f=false|title= Between Rome and Persia: The Middle Euphrates, Mesopotamia and Palmyra under Roman control|author= Peter Edwell|page= 64|year= 2007}}</ref>|group=note}}<ref name="warwik" /> with the Palmyrene merchants establishing colonies in many of the surrounding important trade centers.<ref name="palmoi" />

====Prosperity====
[[File:Grande collonade street06(js).jpg|thumb|The monumental arch in the eastern section of Palmyra's colonnade.]]
The Palmyrene trade reached its apex during the second century.<ref name="palmo55">{{cite book|url=https://books.google.nl/books?id=_LfXg2r6FT0C&pg=PA22#v=onepage&q&f=false|title= The Palmyrenes of Dura-Europos: A Study of Religious Interaction in Roman Syria|author= Lucinda Dirven|page= 22|year= 1999}}</ref> Two factors helped Palmyra achieving its status, the first was the trade route that the Palmyrenes built,<ref name="pliny" /> and protected by maintaining garrisons along the important locations, including a garrison in [[Dura-Europos]] which was stationed by 117.<ref name="ossos">{{cite book|url=https://books.google.nl/books?id=h5cMho6zFckC&pg=PA145#v=onepage&q&f=false|title= Roman Palmyra: Identity, Community, and State Formation|author= Andrew M. Smith II|page= 145|year= 2013}}</ref> The second factor was the Roman [[Arabia Petraea#Roman conquest|annexation]] of the [[Nabataean kingdom|Nabataean]] capital [[Petra]] in 106,<ref name="trev34" /> which led to the collapse of Nabataean control over the southern trade routes from [[Arabia]], and their shifting to Palmyra.{{#tag:ref|Although a mainstream view that Palmyra benefited from Petra's annexation, it should be noted that Palmyra's trade was mostly with the east, while Petra's trade counted on southern Arabia. In addition to the fact that Palmyra's articles of trade were different from Petra, hence the annexation of Petra might have not had a real effect on Palmyra's trade.<ref>{{cite book|url=https://books.google.nl/books?id=E5yCAgAAQBAJ&pg=PA125#v=onepage&q&f=false|title= Rome's Eastern Trade: International Commerce and Imperial Policy 31 BC - AD 305|author= Gary K. Young|page= 125|year= 2003}}</ref>|group=note}}<ref name="trev34" /> 
[[File:Palmyra theater02(js).jpg|thumb|left|Palmyra's theater.]]
In 129, Palmyra was visited by emperor [[Hadrian]], who named it ''Hadriane Palmyra'' and granted it the status of a [[Free city (antiquity)|free city]],<ref name="trev44">{{cite book|url=https://books.google.nl/books?id=Xno9AgAAQBAJ&pg=PA279#v=onepage&q&f=false|title= Ancient Syria: A Three Thousand Year History|author=  Trevor Bryce|page= 279|year= 2014}}</ref><ref name="dirvas6">{{cite book|url=https://books.google.nl/books?id=_LfXg2r6FT0C&pg=PA21#v=onepage&q&f=false|title= The Palmyrenes of Dura-Europos: A Study of Religious Interaction in Roman Syria|author= Lucinda Dirven|page= 21|year= 1999}}</ref> Hadrian promoted [[Hellenization|Hellenism]] throughout the empire,<ref name="smit">{{cite book|url=https://books.google.nl/books?id=h5cMho6zFckC&pg=PA25#v=onepage&q&f=false|title= Roman Palmyra: Identity, Community, and State Formation|author=  Andrew M. Smith II|page= 25|year= 2013}}</ref> and Palmyra's urban expansion was modeled on the Greek fashion,<ref name="smit" /> leading to many new projects, including the [[Roman Theatre at Palmyra|theatre]], the [[Great Colonnade at Palmyra|colonnade]] and the temple of [[Nabu]].<ref name="smit" /> The Roman authority in the city was reinforced in 167, when the garrison [[Auxilia#Alae|Ala I Thracum Herculiana]] was moved to Palmyra.<ref>{{cite book|url=https://books.google.nl/books?id=Ig0_4HeMh-AC&pg=PA881#v=onepage&q&f=false|title= Politische Geschichte: (Provinzien und Randv<U+00F6>lker: Mesopotamien, Armenien, Iran, S<U+00FC>darabien, Rom und der Ferne Osten), Part 2,Volume 9|author= Hildegard Temporini|page= 881|year= 1978}}</ref>

During the third century, Palmyra started a steady transition toward a monarchical system instead of a traditional Greek city-state model,<ref name="camb">{{cite book|url=https://books.google.nl/books?id=MNSyT_PuYVMC&pg=PA512#v=onepage&q&f=false|title= The Cambridge Ancient History: Volume 12, The Crisis of Empire, AD 193-337|author= Alan Bowman,Peter Garnsey,Averil Cameron|page= 512|year= 2005}}</ref> and the urban development diminished,<ref name="smeeto">{{cite book|url=https://books.google.nl/books?id=h5cMho6zFckC&pg=PA26#v=onepage&q&f=false|title= Roman Palmyra: Identity, Community, and State Formation|author=  Andrew M. Smith II|page= 26|year= 2013}}</ref> as the city had reached the apogee of its building projects.<ref name="smeeto" /> The ascendance of the [[Severan dynasty]] to the imperial throne in Rome played a major part in Palmyra's transition.<ref name="smeeto" /> Firstly, the new dynasty favored the city,<ref name="smeeto55">{{cite book|url=https://books.google.nl/books?id=h5cMho6zFckC&pg=PA28#v=onepage&q&f=false|title= Roman Palmyra: Identity, Community, and State Formation|author=  Andrew M. Smith II|page= 28|year= 2013}}</ref> and stationed the [[Auxilia#Cohortes|Cohors I Flavia Chalcidenorum]] as a garrison by 206.<ref>{{cite book|url=https://books.google.nl/books?id=DQgmOZlsEWcC&pg=PA60#v=onepage&q&f=false|title= Between Rome and Persia: The Middle Euphrates, Mesopotamia and Palmyra Under Roman Control|author=Peter Edwell|page= 60|year= 2007}}</ref> Palmyrene militias were given a prominent role in the protection of the Roman frontiers in eastern Syria,<ref name="sasonsz">{{cite book|url=https://books.google.nl/books?id=DQgmOZlsEWcC&pg=PA62#v=onepage&q&f=false|title= Between Rome and Persia: The Middle Euphrates, Mesopotamia and Palmyra Under Roman Control|author=Peter Edwell|page= 62|year= 2007}}</ref> and emperor [[Caracalla]] elevated Palmyra into a [[Colonia (Roman)|Colonia]] between 213 and 216, which brought new constitutional institutions that replaced many of the Greek ones.<ref name="camb" /> Secondly, the Severan led [[Roman<U+2013>Parthian Wars#Hadrian.27s policy.2C and further wars of annexation|Roman-Parthian]] war which lasted from 194 to 217 influenced the regional security and affected the trade of the city.<ref name="smeeto55" /><ref>{{cite book|url=https://books.google.nl/books?id=DQgmOZlsEWcC&pg=PA61#v=onepage&q&f=false|title= Between Rome and Persia: The Middle Euphrates, Mesopotamia and Palmyra Under Roman Control|author=Peter Edwell|page= 61|year= 2007}}</ref> Bandits started to attack the caravans by 199, leading Palmyra to strengthen its military abilities,<ref name="smeeto55" /> and the Palmyrene forces started to get more engaged in the protection of the Roman east instead of protecting the trade,<ref name="sasonsz" /> leading to an increase in the importance of the city,<ref name="sasonsz" /> which was visited by emperor [[Alexander Severus]] before his death in 235.<ref name="smeeto55" />

====Palmyrene kingdom and Persian wars====
[[File:Odenaethus bust.jpg|thumb|Odenaethus' alleged bust.]]
The rise of the [[Sassanid]] dynasty in [[Persia]] damaged the Palmyrene trade considerably.<ref name="adnos">{{cite book|url=https://books.google.nl/books?id=h5cMho6zFckC&pg=PA176#v=onepage&q&f=false|title= Roman Palmyra: Identity, Community, and State Formation|author= Andrew M. Smith II|page= 176|year= 2013}}</ref> The Sassanids disbanded the Palmyrene colonies in their lands,<ref name="adnos" /> and started a full scale war against the Roman empire.<ref name="satno">{{cite book|url=https://books.google.nl/books?id=h5cMho6zFckC&pg=PA29#v=onepage&q&f=false|title= Roman Palmyra: Identity, Community, and State Formation|author= Andrew M. Smith II|page= 29|year= 2013}}</ref> Around 251, [[Odaenathus]] appeared in a document with the titles [[exarch]]os and [[Senate of the Roman Empire|senator]] of Palmyra, sharing these titles with his son [[Hairan]].{{#tag:ref|Odaenathus' rise process is ambiguous, he belonged to the mercantile elite, and might have been elected as chief by the council of the city.<ref>{{cite book|url=https://books.google.nl/books?id=73-JAgAAQBAJ&pg=PA77#v=onepage&q&f=false|title= Rome in the East: The Transformation of an Empire|author= Warwick Ball|page= 77|year= 2002}}</ref>|group=note}}<ref name="camb" /><ref name="adnos56">{{cite book|url=https://books.google.nl/books?id=h5cMho6zFckC&pg=PA131#v=onepage&q&f=false|title= Roman Palmyra: Identity, Community, and State Formation|author= Andrew M. Smith II|page= 131|year= 2013}}</ref> Odaenathus approached [[Shapur I]] of Persia to guarantee the Palmyrene interests in Persia but was rebuffed,<ref name="adnossa">{{cite book|url=https://books.google.nl/books?id=h5cMho6zFckC&pg=PA177#v=onepage&q&f=false|title= Roman Palmyra: Identity, Community, and State Formation|author= Andrew M. Smith II|page= 177|year= 2013}}</ref> and soon had to fight Shapur after the disastrous Roman defeat at the [[Battle of Edessa]] in 260.<ref name="satno">{{cite book|url=https://books.google.nl/books?id=h5cMho6zFckC&pg=PA177#v=onepage&q&f=false|title= Roman Palmyra: Identity, Community, and State Formation|author= Andrew M. Smith II|page= 177|year= 2013}}</ref> The aforementioned battle ended with emperor [[Valerian (emperor)|Valerian]]'s capture and soon <U+2014>[[Macrianus Major]], his sons [[Quietus]] and [[Macrianus Minor|Macrianus]], and [[Balista]] the [[Praetorian prefect|prefect]]<U+2014> rebelled against Valerian's son [[Gallienus]] and usurped the imperial power in Syria.<ref name="vaji">{{cite book|url=https://books.google.nl/books?id=WzOGycVVQLEC&pg=PA398#v=onepage&q&f=false|title=Coinage and History of the Roman Empire, C. 82 B.C.--A.D. 480: History|author= David L. Vagi|page= 398|year= 2000}}</ref> 

Odaenathus remained loyal to Gallienus and formed an army of Palmyrenes, peasants and what remained of the Roman soldiers in the region to resist Shapur.<ref name="satno" /> The Palmyrene leader won a decisive victory over Shapur in a battle near the banks of the Euphrates in 260.<ref name="vaji" /> This was followed by reclaiming the [[Mesopotamia (Roman province)|Roman Mesopotamia]],<ref name="vaji" /> and besieging the Persian capital [[Ctesiphon]].<ref name="trevo586">{{cite book|url=https://books.google.nl/books?id=Xno9AgAAQBAJ&pg=PA287#v=onepage&q&f=false|title= Ancient Syria: A Three Thousand Year History|author= Trevor Bryce|page= 287|year= 2014}}</ref> As a reward, the victorious Palmyrene received the title ''Imperator Totius Orientis'' (Governor of the East) from Gallienus,<ref>{{cite book|url=https://books.google.nl/books?id=q8Z7AgAAQBAJ&pg=PA290#v=onepage&q&f=false|title= Ancient Syria: A Three Thousand Year History|author= Trevor Bryce|page= 290|year= 2014}}</ref> ruling Syria as the imperial representative.<ref name="satnso">{{cite book|url=https://books.google.nl/books?id=y6IaBQAAQBAJ&pg=PA333#v=onepage&q&f=false|title=Syrian Identity in the Greco-Roman World|author=  Nathanael J. Andrade|page= 333|year= 2013}}</ref> Personally, Odaenathus declared himself king or [[King of Kings]],{{#tag:ref|The first decisive evidence for the use of this title is an inscription dated to 271, posthumously describing Odaenathus as ''king of kings''.<ref name="vajisczvd">{{cite book|url=https://books.google.nl/books?id=8kLFfE1qPhIC&pg=PA78#v=onepage&q&f=false|title=Palmyra and Its Empire: Zenobia's Revolt Against Rome|author= Richard Stoneman|page= 78|year= 1994}}</ref><ref name="adnossa" /> However, Odaenathus' own inscriptions address him as king, and it is not certain that he used the king of kings title.<ref name="vajisczvd" />|group=note}}<ref name="vajisczvd9">{{cite book|url=https://books.google.nl/books?id=9y7nTpFcN3AC&pg=PA354#v=onepage&q&f=false|title=The Middle East Under Rome|author= Maurice Sartre|page= 354|year= 2005}}</ref> and in 261, he marched against the remaining usurpers in Syria, defeating and killing Quietus and Balista.<ref name="vaji" /> This was followed by a new war against Persia in 262.<ref>{{cite book|url=https://books.google.nl/books?id=K6eFJ_vcqSwC&pg=PA501#v=onepage&q&f=false|title=The Decline and Fall of the Roman Empire|author= Edward Gibbon|page= 501|year= 2004}}</ref><ref>{{cite book|url=https://books.google.nl/books?id=bpd3tBPN4v8C&pg=PA237#v=onepage&q&f=false|title= Imperial Rome AD 193 to 284: The Critical Century|author= Clifford Ando|page= 237|year= 2012}}</ref>

After defeating a Persian army in 263 or 264, Odaenathus crowned his son Hairan as co-king near Antioch,<ref>{{cite book|url=https://books.google.nl/books?id=0TsSdzpN39MC&pg=PA404#v=onepage&q&f=false|title="Imitation Greeks": Being Syrian in the Greco-Roman World (175 BCE--275 CE).|author= Nathanael John Andrade|page= 404|year= 2009}}</ref> then marched in 264 and [[Battle of Ctesiphon (264)|besieged]] Ctesiphon for the second time.<ref name="fddddddd">{{cite book|url=https://books.google.nl/books?id=7-jUAMmMS5cC&pg=PA3#v=onepage&q&f=false|title=The Policy of the Emperor Gallienus|author= Lukas De Blois|page= 3|year= 1976}}</ref> Although not successful in taking the Persians' capital, Odaenathus drove them out of all the Roman lands they conquered since the beginning of Shapur's [[Siege of Nisibis (252)|wars in 252]].<ref name="fddddddd" /> The Persians unsuccessfully campaigned against Palmyra but were repelled,<ref>{{cite book|url=https://books.google.nl/books?id=566PXereaPsC&pg=PA46#v=onepage&q&f=false|title=Sassanian Elite Cavalry AD 224-642|author= Kaveh Farrokh,Angus McBride|page= 46|year= 2012}}</ref> and then defeated by Odaenathus in 266 near Ctesiphon.<ref name="vaji" /> The Palmyrene monarch then headed north to repel the [[Asia (Roman province)#Decline|Goth's attacks]] on [[Asia Minor]] in 267,<ref name="vaji" /> but was assassinated along with Hairan on their returning way.<ref name="vaji" /> According to the [[Augustan History]] and [[John Zonaras]], Odaenathus was killed by his cousin whose name in the Augustan History is [[Maeonius]].<ref name="maoniasa">{{cite book|url=https://books.google.nl/books?id=DqMrR29Cc7MC&pg=PA78#v=onepage&q&f=false|title=Empress Zenobia: Palmyra s Rebel Queen|author= Pat Southern|page= 78|year= 2008}}</ref> The Augustan History also claims that Maeonius was proclaimed emperor for a very brief period, before being trialed and executed by Odaenathus' widow [[Zenobia]].<ref name="maoniasa" /><ref name="maoni">{{cite book|url=https://books.google.nl/books?id=q8Z7AgAAQBAJ&pg=PA292#v=onepage&q&f=false|title=Ancient Syria: A Three Thousand Year History|author= Trevor Bryce|page= 292|year= 2014}}</ref><ref>{{cite book|url=https://books.google.nl/books?id=8kLFfE1qPhIC&pg=PA108#v=onepage&q&f=false|title=Palmyra and Its Empire: Zenobia's Revolt Against Rome|author= Richard Stoneman|page= 108|year= 1994}}</ref> However, no inscriptions or other evidence exist for Maeonius reign, and he was probably killed immediately after assassinating Odaenathus.<ref>{{cite book|url=https://books.google.nl/books?id=dlEMAQAAMAAJ&pg=PA321#v=onepage&q&f=false|title=History of the decline and fall of the Roman empire for the use of families and young persons: reprinted from the original text, with the careful omission of all passagers of an irreligious tendency, Volume 1|author= Edward Gibbon, Thomas Bowdler|page= 321|year= 1826}}</ref><ref>{{cite book|url=https://books.google.nl/books?id=0mloAAAAMAAJ&q|title=The Age of the Soldier Emperors: Imperial Rome, A.D. 244-284|author= George C. Brauer|page= 163|year= 1975}}</ref>

=====Palmyrene empire=====
{{Main|Palmyrene Empire}}
[[File:Palmyra imposed.png|thumb|left|The Palmyrene empire.]]
Odaenathus was succeeded by his ten-year-old son [[Vaballathus]] under the regency of Zenobia, the mother of the new king.<ref name="zenok">{{cite book|url=https://books.google.nl/books?id=Xno9AgAAQBAJ&pg=PA299#v=onepage&q&f=false|title=Ancient Syria: A Three Thousand Year History|author= Trevor Bryce|page= 299|year= 2014}}</ref> Zenobia was the real ruler of Palmyra, and Vaballathus remained in the shadow while his mother consolidated her power.<ref name="zenok" /> The queen was careful not to provoke Rome and claimed for herself and her son the titles that her husband had, while working on guaranteeing the safety of the borders with Persia, and pacifying the dangerous [[Tanukhid]] tribes in [[Hauran]].<ref name="zenok" />
[[File:AURELIANUS RIC V 381-795833.jpg|thumb|Vaballathus (right) as king on the obverse of an [[Antoninianus]]. To the left, Aurelian as Augustus on the reverse.]]
Zenobia started her military career in the spring of 270, during the reign of emperor [[Claudius II]].<ref name="zenok1988">{{cite book|url=https://books.google.nl/books?id=41-MAgAAQBAJ&pg=PA302#v=onepage&q&f=false|title=Ancient Syria: A Three Thousand Year History|author= Trevor Bryce|page= 302|year= 2014}}</ref> Under the cover of attacking the Tanukhids, Zenobia annexed the [[Arabia Petraea|Roman Arabia]].<ref name="zenok1988" /> This was followed in October of 270 by an invasion of [[Egypt (Roman province)|Egypt]],<ref name="zenok5saa">{{cite book|url=https://books.google.nl/books?id=kJ2JAgAAQBAJ&pg=PA62#v=onepage&q&f=false|title=Aurelian and the Third Century|author= Alaric Watson|page= 62|year= 2014}}</ref><ref>{{cite book|url=https://books.google.nl/books?id=41-MAgAAQBAJ&pg=PA303#v=onepage&q&f=false|title=Ancient Syria: A Three Thousand Year History|author= Trevor Bryce|page= 303|year= 2014}}</ref> that ended with a Palmyrene victory and Zenobia's proclamation as queen of Egypt.<ref name="zenok3">{{cite book|url=https://books.google.nl/books?id=Xno9AgAAQBAJ&pg=PA304#v=onepage&q&f=false|title=Ancient Syria: A Three Thousand Year History|author= Trevor Bryce|page= 304|year= 2014}}</ref> Afterward, Palmyra invaded [[Asia Minor]] in 271 and reached [[Ankara]], marking the greatest extent of the Palmyrene expansion.<ref name="waro">{{cite book|url=https://books.google.nl/books?id=qQKIAgAAQBAJ&pg=PA80#v=onepage&q&f=false|title=Rome in the East: The Transformation of an Empire|author= Warwick Ball|page= 80|year= 2002}}</ref> 

Those conquests were conducted under the mask of subordination to Rome,<ref name="zenok5">{{cite book|url=https://books.google.nl/books?id=h5cMho6zFckC&pg=PA179#v=onepage&q&f=false|title= Roman Palmyra: Identity, Community, and State Formation|author= Andrew M. Smith II|page= 179|year= 2013}}</ref> Zenobia issued the coinage in the name of Claudius' successor [[Aurelian]] as emperor, with Vaballathus depicted as king,{{#tag:ref|Claudius died in August 270, shortly before Zenobia's invasion of Egypt.<ref name="zenok5saa" />|group=note}} while Aurelian allowed the Palmyrene coinage and conferred the Palmyrene royal titles, as he was occupied in repelling numerous insurgencies in [[Europe]].<ref name="zenok556">{{cite book|url=https://books.google.nl/books?id=WzOGycVVQLEC&pg=PA365&lpg=PA365#v=onepage&q&f=false|title=Coinage and History of the Roman Empire, C. 82 B.C.--A.D. 480: History|author= David L. Vagi|page= 365|year= 2000}}</ref> Toward the end of 271, Vaballathus took the title of [[Augustus (honorific)|Augustus]] (emperor) along with his mother.{{#tag:ref|[[Palmyrene Empire#Evaluation and legacy|Scholarly is divided]] whether this was an act of independence declaration, or a usurpation of the Roman throne.<ref name="zenok65">{{cite book|url=https://books.google.nl/books?id=73-JAgAAQBAJ&pg=PA82#v=onepage&q&f=false|title=Rome in the East: The Transformation of an Empire|author= Warwick Ball|page= 82|year= 2002}}</ref><ref name="zenok69">{{cite book|url=https://books.google.nl/books?id=GSmrBAAAQBAJ&pg=PT154#v=onepage&q&f=false|title=The New Cambridge History of Islam: Volume 1, The Formation of the Islamic World, Sixth to Eleventh Centuries|author= Chase F. Robinson|page= 154|year= 2010}}</ref><ref name="waro56">{{cite book|url=https://books.google.nl/books?id=h5cMho6zFckC&pg=PA180#v=onepage&q&f=false|title= Roman Palmyra: Identity, Community, and State Formation|author= Andrew M. Smith II|page= 180|year= 2013}}</ref>|group=note}}<ref name="zenok5" /> 

In 272, Aurelian crossed the [[Bosphorus]] and advanced quickly through [[Anatolia]].<ref>{{cite book|url=https://books.google.nl/books?id=Xno9AgAAQBAJ&pg=PA307#v=onepage&q&f=false|title=Ancient Syria: A Three Thousand Year History|author= Trevor Bryce|page= 307|year= 2014}}</ref> According to one account, Roman general [[Marcus Aurelius Probus]] regained Egypt from Palmyra,{{#tag:ref|All other accounts indicate that a military action was not necessary, as it seems that Zenobia's withdrawn her forces in order to defend Syria.<ref name="zenok29">{{cite book|url=https://books.google.nl/books?id=Xno9AgAAQBAJ&pg=PA308#v=onepage&q&f=false|title=Ancient Syria: A Three Thousand Year History|author= Trevor Bryce|page= 308|year= 2014}}</ref>|group=note}}<ref name="zenok29" /> while Aurelian continued his march entering [[Issus (town)|Issus]] and heading to [[Antioch]], where he defeated Zenobia in the [[Battle of Immae]].<ref>{{cite book|url=https://books.google.nl/books?id=Xno9AgAAQBAJ&pg=PA309#v=onepage&q&f=false|title=Ancient Syria: A Three Thousand Year History|author= Trevor Bryce|page= 309|year= 2014}}</ref> Zenobia was defeated again at the [[Battle of Emesa]] and took refuge in the [[Homs|city]], but evacuated quickly back to her capital.<ref>{{cite book|url=https://books.google.nl/books?id=Xno9AgAAQBAJ&pg=PA310#v=onepage&q&f=false|title=Ancient Syria: A Three Thousand Year History|author= Trevor Bryce|page= 310|year= 2014}}</ref> The Romans besieged Palmyra and tried to negotiate with Zenobia, on the condition that she surrender herself in person to the emperor, to which she answered with refusal.<ref name="waro" /> The empress escaped the city and headed east to ask the Persians for help, but was captured and soon after, the city capitulated.<ref name="waro45">{{cite book|url=https://books.google.nl/books?id=qQKIAgAAQBAJ&pg=PA81#v=onepage&q&f=false|title=Rome in the East: The Transformation of an Empire|author= Warwick Ball|page= 81|year= 2002}}</ref><ref>{{cite book|url=https://books.google.nl/books?id=MNSyT_PuYVMC&pg=PA52#v=onepage&q&f=false|title=The Cambridge Ancient History: Volume 12, The Crisis of Empire, AD 193-337|author= Alan Bowman,Peter Garnsey,Averil Cameron|page= 52|year= 2005}}</ref>

====Later Roman and Byzantine periods====
[[File:Diocletian's Camp, Palmyra 01.jpg|thumb|Diocletian's camp.]]
Aurelian spared the city and stationed a garrison of 600 archers led by a certain [[Sandarion]], as a peacekeeping force.<ref>{{cite book|url=https://books.google.nl/books?id=Xno9AgAAQBAJ&pg=PA313#v=onepage&q&f=false|title= Ancient Syria: A Three Thousand Year History|author= Trevor Bryce|page= 313|year= 2014}}</ref> However, in 273, Palmyra rebelled under the leadership of a citizen named [[Septimius Apsaios]],<ref name="waro56" /> and declared a relative of Zenobia named [[Antiochus of Palmyra|Antiochus]] as Augustus.<ref name="destao54">{{cite book|url=https://books.google.nl/books?id=h5cMho6zFckC&pg=PA181#v=onepage&q&f=false|title= Roman Palmyra: Identity, Community, and State Formation|author= Andrew M. Smith II|page= 181|year= 2013}}</ref> Aurelian marched against Palmyra and this time razed it to the ground,<ref name="camb66">{{cite book|url=https://books.google.nl/books?id=MNSyT_PuYVMC&pg=PA515#v=onepage&q&f=false|title= The Cambridge Ancient History: Volume 12, The Crisis of Empire, AD 193-337|author= Alan Bowman,Peter Garnsey,Averil Cameron|page= 515|year= 2005}}</ref> the most valuable monuments were taken by the emperor to decorate his [[Sol Invictus#Aurelian|Temple of Sol]],<ref name="waro45" /> while Palmyrene buildings were smashed, people were clubbed and cudgeled and the temple of Bel pillaged.<ref name="waro45" />

Palmyra was reduced to a village with no territory to rule, Aurelian repaired the temple of Bel, and the [[List of Roman legions#Late Empire legions|Legio I Illyricorum]] was stationed in the city.<ref name="destao">{{cite book|url=https://books.google.nl/books?id=2ijMkjyG3cQC&pg=PA298#v=onepage&q&f=false|title= Soldiers, Cities, and Civilians in Roman Syria|author= Nigel Pollard|page= 298|year= 2000}}</ref> Shortly before 303, the [[Camp of Diocletian]], a [[Castra]] in the western side of the city was built.<ref name="destao" /> The camp enclosed an area of four hectares as a military base for the Legio I Illyricorum,<ref name="destao" /> which guarded the trade routes around the city.<ref name="destao6">{{cite book|url=https://books.google.nl/books?id=2ijMkjyG3cQC&pg=PA299#v=onepage&q&f=false|title= Soldiers, Cities, and Civilians in Roman Syria|author= Nigel Pollard|page= 299|year= 2000}}</ref>

Palmyra became a [[Christianity|Christian]] city in the decades following the destruction by Aurelian.<ref name="desto89">{{cite book|url=https://books.google.nl/books?id=8kLFfE1qPhIC&pg=PA190#v=onepage&q&f=false|title= Palmyra and Its Empire: Zenobia's Revolt Against Rome|author= Richard Stoneman|page= 190|year= 1994}}</ref> In late 527, [[Justinian I]] ordered the fortification of Palmyra, and the restoring of its churches and public buildings.<ref name="desto645">{{cite book|url=https://books.google.nl/books?id=awCGAgAAQBAJ&pg=PA85#v=onepage&q&f=false|title= The Roman Eastern Frontier and the Persian Wars AD 363-628|author= Geoffrey Greatrex,Samuel N. C. Lieu|page= 85|year= 2005}}</ref> This was a step to protect the empire against the raids of the [[Lakhmid]] king [[Al-Mundhir III ibn al-Nu'man]].<ref name="desto645" />

===Arab caliphate===
Palmyra was captured by the [[Rashidun Caliphate]] under [[Khalid ibn al-Walid]] in 634, and by then, it was limited to the Diocletian camp.<ref name="desto8s9sa">{{cite book|url=https://books.google.nl/books?id=R44VRnNCzAYC&pg=PA568#v=onepage&q&f=false|title=Middle East and Africa: International Dictionary of Historic Places|author=  Trudy Ring,Noelle Watson,Paul Schellinger|page= 568|year= 2014}}</ref> Palmyra witnessed some prosperity during the [[Ummayad]] era,<ref>{{cite book|url=https://books.google.nl/books?id=Q6ppv17CP6EC&pg=PA87#v=onepage&q&f=false|title=The Idea and Ideal of the Town Between Late Antiquity and the Early Middle Ages|author=  Gian Pietro Brogiolo,Bryan Ward Perkins|page= 87|year= 1999}}</ref> but had its walls demolished by caliph [[Marwan II]] in 745 due to a local revolt.<ref name="desto8s9sa" /><ref>{{cite book|url=https://books.google.nl/books?id=2C6KIBw4F9YC&pg=PA73#v=onepage&q&f=false|title=White Banners: Contention in 'Abbasid Syria, 750-880|author= Paul M. Cobb|page= 73|year= 2001}}</ref> In 750, a revolt against the newly established [[Abbasid]] dynasty, led by [[Majza'a ibn al-Kawthar ]] and an Ummayad pretender named [[Abu-Muhammad al-Sufyani]], swept across Syria,<ref name="umaj">{{cite book|url=https://books.google.nl/books?id=2C6KIBw4F9YC&pg=PA47#v=onepage&q&f=false|title= White Banners: Contention in 'Abbasid Syria, 750-880|author= Paul M. Cobb|page= 47|year= 2001}}</ref> and the tribes of Palmyra supported the rebels.<ref name="umaj2">{{cite book|url=https://books.google.nl/books?id=2C6KIBw4F9YC&pg=PA48#v=onepage&q&f=false|title= White Banners: Contention in 'Abbasid Syria, 750-880|author= Paul M. Cobb|page= 48|year= 2001}}</ref> After being defeated, Abu-Muhammad took refuge in the Palmyra, which withstand the Abbasid attack long enough, giving the rebel a chance to escape.<ref name="umaj2" />

====Decentralized caliphate====
Abbasid power dwindled in the 10th century, the empire disintegrated and was divided between different vassals.<ref>{{cite book|url=https://books.google.nl/books?id=TqasAgAAQBAJ&pg=PA13#v=onepage&q&f=false|title= The Age of the Crusades: The Near East from the Eleventh Century to 1517|author=  P.M. Holt|page= 13|year= 2014}}</ref> Most of the new rulers acknowledged the caliph as their nominal sovereign, a situation that continued until the [[Siege of Baghdad (1258)|Mongol destruction]] of the Abbasid caliphate in 1258.<ref>{{cite book|url=https://books.google.nl/books?id=9lHeh36S8ooC&pg=PT1531#v=onepage&q&f=false|title= The Cambridge Medieval History Series volumes 1-5|author=  J.B. Bury|page= 1531|year= 2011}}</ref> 
[[File:Gate of the fortified Temple of Bel Palmyra Syria.jpg|left|thumb|Bel's temple fortifications.]]
In 955, [[Sayf al-Dawla]], the [[Hamdanid dynasty|Hamdanid]] prince of [[Aleppo]], defeated the nomads near the city,<ref>{{cite book|url=https://books.google.nl/books?id=QMSCNQlywSsC&pg=PA11#v=onepage&q&f=false|title= City in the Desert|author= Oleg Grabar,Reneta Holod,James Knustad,William Trousdale|page= 11|year= 1978}}</ref> and built a [[Kasbah]] (fortress) in response to the [[Arab<U+2013>Byzantine wars#Byzantine resurgence.2C 863.E2.80.9311th century|campaigns]] of the Byzantine emperors [[Nikephoros II Phokas]] and [[John I Tzimiskes]].<ref name="umaj3">{{cite book|url=https://books.google.nl/books?id=QMSCNQlywSsC&pg=PA158#v=onepage&q&f=false|title= City in the Desert|author= Oleg Grabar,Reneta Holod,James Knustad,William Trousdale|page= 158|year= 1978}}</ref> Following the Hamdanids demise in the beginning of the 11th century, Palmyra was controlled by their successors the [[Mirdasid dynasty|Mirdasids]].<ref>{{cite book|url=https://books.google.nl/books?id=k-gKAAAAIAAJ&q|title=Rubu' Mu<U+1E25>afazet <U+1E25>oms|language= ar|author= <U+02BB>Im<U+0101>d al-D<U+012B>n Maw<U+1E63><U+012B>l<U+012B>|page= 221|year= 1981}}</ref> Earthquakes devastated the city in 1068 and 1089.<ref name="desto8s9sa" /><ref>{{cite book|url=https://books.google.nl/books?id=UC5v4mgERxwC&pg=PA184#v=onepage&q&f=false|title= The Barbarian Plain: Saint Sergius Between Rome and Iran|author= Elizabeth Key Fowden|page= 184|year= 1999}}</ref> The Mirdasids were followed in the second half of the 11th century, by prince [[Khalaf ibn Malaieb|Khalaf]] of the [[Mala'ib]] tribe centered in [[Homs]].<ref>{{cite book|url=https://books.google.nl/books?id=VWJIAAAAMAAJ&dq|title=Banu Mala'ib fel-Tarikh|language= ar|author= Mahmud Hussein Amin|page= 50|year= 1998}}</ref> However, in the 1070's, the whole of Syria came under the authority of the [[Seljuk Empire|Seljuks]],<ref>{{cite book|url=https://books.google.nl/books?id=1ioTXW3316AC&pg=PA148#v=onepage&q&f=false|title= A Companion to the History of the Middle East|author= Youssef M. Choueiri|page= 148|year= 2008}}</ref> whose sultan [[Malik-Shah I]] expelled the Mala'ib and imprisoned Khalaf in 1090.<ref name="mala3">{{cite book|url=https://books.google.nl/books?id=2q4KAQAAIAAJ&q|title=Bughyat al-<U+1E6D>alab f<U+012B> t<U+0101>r<U+012B>kh <U+1E24>alab. Volume 3|language= ar|author= Ibn al-<U+02BB>Adim|page= 365|year= 1261}}</ref> Khalaf's lands were rewarded to Malik-Shah's brother [[Tutush I]],<ref name="mala3" /> who gained his independence following his brother's death in 1092, establishing a [[List of Seljuk rulers in Syria (1076<U+2013>1117)|cadet branch]] of the Seljuq dynasty in Syria.<ref>{{cite book|url=https://books.google.nl/books?id=nDVOR7jZYJEC&pg=PA135#v=onepage&q&f=false|title= Putting the Caliph in His Place: Power, Authority, and the Late Abbasid Caliphate|author= Eric J. Hanne|page= 135|year= 2007}}</ref>
[[File:Qalat ibn maan01(js).jpg|thumb|Fakhr-al-Din al-Maani Castle.]]
In the early 12th century, Palmyra came under the authority of [[Toghtekin]], the [[Burid dynasty|Burid]] [[Atabeg]] of Damascus, who appointed his nephew as a governor.<ref name="umaj23">{{cite book|url=https://books.google.nl/books?id=oaTDAgAAQBAJ&pg=PA178#v=onepage&q&f=false|title= The Damascus Chronicle of the Crusades: Extracted and Translated from the Chronicle of Ibn Al-Qalanisi|author= H. A. R. Gibb|page= 178|year= 2012}}</ref> Toghtekin's nephew was killed, causing the Atabeg to march and retake the city in 1126.<ref name="umaj23" /> Then Palmyra was given to Toghtekin's grandson, [[Shihab-ud-din Mahmud]],<ref name="umaj23" /> who was replaced by a governor named [[Yusuf ibn Firuz]],<ref name="umaj23s">{{cite book|url=https://books.google.nl/books?id=HOzgoAEACAAJ&dq|title=Tarikh Abu Yala Hamza Ibn al-Qalanisi al-maruf Bi-Dhail tarikh Dimashq: tatluh nukhab min tawarikh Ibn al-Azraq al-Fariqi wa-Sibt ibn al-Giawzi wa-l-Hafiz al-Dhahbi|language= ar|author= Abu Yala Hazma ibn Asad al-Tamini Ibn al-Qalanisi, H. F. Amedroz|page= 73|year= 1908}}</ref> after the former went back to Damascus following his father [[Taj al-Muluk Buri]]'s succession.<ref name="umaj23s" /> The Burids turned the temple of Bel into a citadel in 1132 and fortified the city,<ref>{{cite book|url=https://books.google.nl/books?id=QMSCNQlywSsC&pg=PA161#v=onepage&q&f=false|title= City in the Desert|author= Oleg Grabar,Reneta Holod,James Knustad,William Trousdale|page= 161|year= 1978}}</ref><ref name="umaj2346">{{cite book|url=https://books.google.nl/books?id=oaTDAgAAQBAJ&pg=PA237#v=onepage&q&f=false|title= The Damascus Chronicle of the Crusades: Extracted and Translated from the Chronicle of Ibn Al-Qalanisi|author= H. A. R. Gibb|page= 237|year= 2012}}</ref> then transferred it to the [[Bin Qaraja]] family in 1135 in exchange for [[Homs]].<ref name="umaj2346" /> 

In the middle of the 12th century, the city was incorporated to the realm of the [[Zengid dynasty|Zengid]] king [[Nur ad-Din, atabeg of Aleppo|Nur ad-Din Mahmud]].<ref>{{cite book|url=https://books.google.nl/books?id=pAVSygAACAAJ&dq|title=Siyar a<U+02BB>l<U+0101>m an-nubal<U+0101><U+00B7>, Volume 20|language= ar|author=Mu<U+1E25>ammad Ibn-A<U+1E25>mad ad<U+0332>- D<U+0332>ahab<U+012B>|page= 533|year= 1338}}</ref> It became part of Homs district,<ref>{{cite book|url=https://books.google.nl/books?id=waFtAAAAMAAJ&q|title= Bulletin d'<U+00E9>tudes orientales, Volume 51|author= Institut fran<U+00E7>ais de Damas|page= 161|year= 1999}}</ref> which was given as a fiefdom to the Ayyubid general [[Shirkuh]] in 1167,<ref>{{cite book|url=https://books.google.nl/books?id=pAVSygAACAAJ&dq|title=Siyar a<U+02BB>l<U+0101>m an-nubal<U+0101><U+00B7>, Volume 20|language= ar|author=Mu<U+1E25>ammad Ibn-A<U+1E25>mad ad<U+0332>- D<U+0332>ahab<U+012B>|page= 430|year= 1338}}</ref> but confiscated following his death in 1169.<ref>{{cite book|url=https://books.google.nl/books?id=G9jnL131V3UC&pg=PA72#v=onepage&q&f=false|title=Saladin|author= Andrew S. Ehrenkreutz|page= 72|year= 1972}}</ref> Homs district was annexed by the [[Ayyubid dynasty|Ayyubid sultanate]] in 1174,<ref>{{cite book|url=https://books.google.nl/books?id=DZU-AQAAIAAJ&q|title=Al-mukhta<U+1E63>ar f<U+012B> akhb<U+0101>r al-bashar, Volumes 1-2|language= ar|author=Ab<U+016B> al-Fid<U+0101><U+02BC> Ism<U+0101><U+02BB><U+012B>l ibn <U+02BB>Al<U+012B>|page= 349|year= 1331}}</ref> and in 1175, Sultan [[Saladin]] gave Homs including Palmyra as a fiefdom to his cousin [[Muhammad ibn Shirkuh|Nasir al-Din Muhammad]].<ref>{{cite book|url=https://books.google.nl/books?id=JfXl5kvabhoC&pg=PA51#v=onepage&q&f=false|title=From Saladin to the Mongols: The Ayyubids of Damascus, 1193-1260|author= R. Stephen Humphreys|page= 51|year= 1977}}</ref> Following Saladin death, the Ayyubid realm was divided and the city was conferred upon Nasir al-Din Muhammad's son [[Al-Mujahid|Al-Mujahid Shirkuh II]],<ref>{{cite book|url=https://books.google.nl/books?id=1m4fbJyQ4pkC&pg=PA62#v=onepage&q&f=false|title=The Crusades and the Military Orders: Expanding the Frontiers of Medieval Latin Christianity|author=Zsolt Hunyadi, J<U+00F3>zsef Laszlovszky|page= 62|year= 2001}}</ref> who built the castle of Palmyra commonly known as [[Fakhr-al-Din al-Maani Castle]] in c. 1230.<ref name="umaj2asaaa3">{{cite book|url=https://books.google.nl/books?id=z_IBAwAAQBAJ&pg=PA243#v=onepage&q&f=false|title=Monuments of Syria: A Guide|author=Ross Burns|page= 243|year= 2009}}</ref>

===Mamluk period===
Palmyra was used as a refuge by Sherkoh II's grandson [[Al-Ashraf Musa, Emir of Homs|Al-Ashraf Musa]], who allied himself with the [[Mongol Empire|Mongol]] king [[Hulagu Khan]], but fled after the Mongols defeat in [[Battle of Ain Jalut|Ain Jalut]] 1260.<ref name="udsa">{{cite book|url=https://books.google.nl/books?id=JfXl5kvabhoC&pg=PA360#v=onepage&q&f=false|title=From Saladin to the Mongols: The Ayyubids of Damascus, 1193-1260|author=R. Stephen Humphreys|page= 360|year= 1977}}</ref> Al-Ashraf Musa asked the [[Mamluk Sultanate (Cairo)|Mamluk]] sultan [[Qutuz]] for pardon and was accepted by the latter as a vassal, bringing Palmyra to the realm of the Mamluks.<ref name="udsa" /> 

====Al-Fadl principality====
[[File:Palmyra Ruins - Flickr - edbrambley.jpg|thumb|left|Palmyra's gardens.]]
Al-Fadl clan, a branch of the [[Tayy]] tribe, declared its loyalty to the Mamluks,<ref name="babee">{{cite book|url=https://books.google.nl/books?id=lZggAAAAMAAJ&q|title=al-A<U+02BB>l<U+0101>m,: q<U+0101>m<U+016B>s tar<U+0101>jim al-ash<U+02BE>hur al-rij<U+0101>l wa-al-nis<U+0101><U+02BE> min al-<U+02BB>Arab wa-al-musta<U+02BB>rab<U+012B>n wa-al-mustashriq<U+012B>n, Volume 7|language= ar|author= Khayr al-D<U+012B>n Zirikl<U+012B>|page= 73|year= 1926}}</ref><ref>{{cite book|url=https://books.google.nl/books?id=3St6D8PC4tcC&pg=PA30#v=onepage&q&f=false|title=Acre 1291: Bloody Sunset of the Crusader States|author=David Nicolle|page= 30|year= 2005}}</ref> and in 1284, [[Muhanna bin Issa]], the prince of the tribe, was appointed by sultan [[Al Mansur Qalawun|Qalawun]] as the lord of Palmyra.<ref name="babee" /> However, he was imprisoned by sultan [[Al-Ashraf Khalil]] in 1293, then restored in 1295 by sultan [[Al-Adil Kitbugha]].<ref name="babee" /> Muhanna declared his loyalty to [[<U+00D6>ljait<U+00FC>]] of the [[Ilkhanate]] in 1312 and was dismissed by sultan [[Al-Nasir Muhammad]], who replaced him by his brother [[Fadl (Palmyra)|Fadl]].<ref name="babee" /> Muhanna asked Al-Nasir forgiveness and was restored in 1317, only to be expelled with his whole tribe and be replaced by another tribal chief named [[Muhammad ibn Abi Bakr (chief)|Muhammad ibn Abi Bakr]], for his continuing relations with the Ilkhanate.<ref name="babee" /><ref>{{cite book|url=https://books.google.nl/books?id=6atmAAAAMAAJ&q|title=Kit<U+0101>b al-<U+02BB>ibar wa-d<U+012B>w<U+0101>n al-mubtada<U+02BE> wa-al-khabar f<U+0323><U+012B> ayy<U+0101>m al-<U+02BB>Arab wa-al-<U+02BB>Ajam <U+1E89>a-al-Barbar wa-man <U+02BB><U+0101><U+1E63>arahum min dhaw<U+012B> al-sul<U+1E6D><U+0101>n al-al-akbar wa-huwa tar<U+012B>kh wa<U+1E25><U+012B>d <U+02BB>a<U+1E63>rih, Volume 5|language= ar|author= Ibn Khald<U+016B>n|page= 104|year= 1375}}</ref>
[[File:01 tadmor old village.jpg|thumb|The village inside the temple of Bel, early 20th century.]]
Muhanna was forgiven and restored by Al-Nasir in 1330, he remained loyal to the sultan, dying in 1333, and was succeeded by his son.<ref name="khalo">{{cite book|url=https://books.google.nl/books?id=6atmAAAAMAAJ&q|title=Kit<U+0101>b al-<U+02BB>ibar wa-d<U+012B>w<U+0101>n al-mubtada<U+02BE> wa-al-khabar f<U+0323><U+012B> ayy<U+0101>m al-<U+02BB>Arab wa-al-<U+02BB>Ajam <U+1E89>a-al-Barbar wa-man <U+02BB><U+0101><U+1E63>arahum min dhaw<U+012B> al-sul<U+1E6D><U+0101>n al-al-akbar wa-huwa tar<U+012B>kh wa<U+1E25><U+012B>d <U+02BB>a<U+1E63>rih, Volume 5 - Part 30|language= ar|author= Ibn Khald<U+016B>n|page= 105|year= 1375}}</ref> Historian [[Chihab al-Umari|Ibn Fadlallah al-Omari]] described the city as boasting "vast gardens, flourishing trades and bizarre monuments".<ref name="khalosa">{{cite book|url=https://books.google.nl/books?id=NAITAQAAMAAJ&q|title=al-Maws<U+016B><U+02BB>ah al-<U+02BB>Arab<U+012B>yah|language= ar|author= Commission of the Arabic Encyclopedia|page= 230|year= 1998}}</ref> The Fadl family protected the trade routes and the villages from [[Bedouin]] raids,<ref name="batuta">{{cite book|url=https://books.google.nl/books?id=u5YVAAAAYAAJ&q|title=Kit<U+0101>b ri<U+1E25>lat Ibn Ba<U+1E6D><U+016B><U+1E6D>ah al-musamm<U+0101>h Tu<U+1E25>fat al-nu<U+1E93><U+1E93><U+0101>r f<U+012B> ghar<U+0101><U+02BE>ib al-am<U+1E63><U+0101>r wa-<U+02BB>aj<U+0101><U+02BE>ib al-asf<U+0101>r|language= ar|author= Ibn Batuta|page= 79|year= 1355}}</ref> but conducted raids against other cities themselves, and fought between each others, causing the Mamluks to interfere militarily, dismissing, imprisoning or expelling the leaders on several occasions.<ref name="khalo" /> In 1400, Palmyra was attacked by [[Timur]],<ref>{{cite book|url=https://books.google.nl/books?id=DzM_AQAAMAAJ&pg=PA222#v=onepage&q&f=false|title=The Encyclopaedia Britannica: Or, Dictionary of Arts, Sciences, and General Literature, Volume 17|author= Thomas Stewart Traill|page= 222|year= 1859}}</ref> who took 200,000 sheep,<ref>{{cite book|url=https://books.google.nl/books?id=RRJVAAAAYAAJ&pg=PA817#v=onepage&q&f=false|title=A cyclopaedia of Biblical literature|author= Henry Burgess|page= 817|year= 1856}}</ref> and destroyed the city.<ref name="khalosaas">{{cite book|url=https://books.google.nl/books?id=43AaAAAAIAAJ&q|title=Baalbek, Palmyra|author= David Moore Robinson|page= 10|year= 1946}}</ref> The Fadl prince, [[Nu'air]], escaped the fight with Timur, then fought against [[List of rulers of Aleppo#Mamluks|Jakam]], the sultan of Aleppo.<ref name="khalaso">{{cite book|url=https://books.google.nl/books?id=zd9MAQAAIAAJ&q|title=Inb<U+0101><U+02BC> al-ghumr bi-abn<U+0101><U+02BC> al-<U+02BB>umr, Volume 5|language= ar|author= A<U+1E25>mad ibn <U+02BB>Al<U+012B> Ibn <U+1E24>ajar al-<U+02BB>Asqal<U+0101>n<U+012B>|page= 349|year= 1446}}</ref> Nu'air was captured, taken to Aleppo and executed in 1406, which according to [[Ibn Hajar al-Asqalani]], broke the Fadl family power.<ref name="khalaso" />

===Ottoman and later periods===
Syria became part of the [[Ottoman empire]] in 1516,<ref>{{cite book|url=https://books.google.nl/books?id=9A-EAgAAQBAJ&pg=PA272#v=onepage&q&f=false|title=Dictionary of Islamic Architecture|author= Andrew Petersen|page= 272|year= 2002}}</ref> and Palmyra was incorporated into the [[Eyalet of Damascus]], and made the center of a [[Sanjak|Salyane Sanjak]].{{#tag:ref|The Salyane Sanjak had an annual allowance from the government, in contrast to the Khas Sanjaks, which yielded a land revenue.<ref name="babsee">{{cite book|url=https://books.google.nl/books?id=66hCAAAAcAAJ&pg=PA93#v=onepage&q&f=false|title=Narrative of Travels in Europe, Asia, and Africa in the Seventeenth Century, Volume 1|author=Evliya <U+00C7>elebi, Joseph Freiherr von Hammer-Purgstall|page= 93|year= 1834}}</ref>|group=note}}<ref name="babsee" />
During the Ottoman period, Palmyra was a small village restricted to the court of Bel's temple.<ref name="babseeasad">{{cite book|url=https://books.google.nl/books?id=fWNpIGNFz0IC&pg=PA1021#v=onepage&q&f=false|title=First Encyclopaedia of Islam: 1913-1936|author= M. Th.Houtsma, T.W.Arnold, R.Basset and R.Hartmann|page= 1021|year= 1993}}</ref> After 1568, the Ottomans appointed the [[Lebanese people|Lebanese]] prince [[Harfush clan|Ali bin Musa Harfush]] as governor of Palmyra's Sanjak,<ref>{{cite book|url=https://books.google.nl/books?id=KGeuAeFFJCEC&pg=PA43#v=onepage&q&f=false|title=The Shiites of Lebanon under Ottoman Rule, 1516<U+2013>1788|author= Stefan Winter|page= 43|year= 2010}}</ref> then dismissed him in 1584 for treason.<ref>{{cite book|url=https://books.google.nl/books?id=KGeuAeFFJCEC&pg=PA48#v=onepage&q&f=false|title=The Shiites of Lebanon under Ottoman Rule, 1516<U+2013>1788|author= Stefan Winter|page= 48|year= 2010}}</ref> 

In 1630, the city came under the authority of another Lebanese prince, [[Fakhr-al-Din II]],<ref name="faho">{{cite book|url=https://books.google.nl/books?id=J-EvNaeh6gsC&pg=PA103#v=onepage&q&f=false|title=Lebanon: A History, 600-2011|author=William Harris|page= 103|year= 2012}}</ref> who renovated Sherkoh II's castle,<ref>{{cite book|url=https://books.google.nl/books?id=5gYNAQAAMAAJ&q|title=Polish Archaeology in the Mediterranean, Volume 7|author=Michal Gawlikowski and Wiktor A. Daszewski|page= 146|year= 1995}}</ref> which became known as [[Fakhr-al-Din al-Maani Castle]].<ref name="umaj2asaaa3" /> The prince fell from grace with the Ottomans in 1633 and lost control over Palmyra,<ref name="faho" /> which remained a Sanjak until incorporated to [[Zor Sanjak|Deir ez-Zor Sanjak]] in 1857.<ref>{{cite book|url=https://books.google.nl/books?id=CioOAQAAMAAJ&q|title=The Encyclop<U+00E6>dia Britannica: A Dictionary of Arts, Sciences, Literature and General Information, Volume 7|author=Hugh Chisholm|page= 933|year= 1910}}</ref> Palmyra became the center of an Ottoman garrison to control the Bedouins in 1867.<ref name="fahso">{{cite book|url=https://books.google.nl/books?id=g1eQAgAAQBAJ&pg=PA143#v=onepage&q&f=false|title=Romes Desert Frontiers|author=David Kennedy,Derrick Riley|page= 143|year= 2012}}</ref>

Palmyra regained some of its importance in the beginning of the 20th century, as a station for caravans whose revival was helped by the arrival of the motorized vehicles.<ref name="babseeasad" /> In 1918, as the [[World War I]] was coming to an end, the [[Royal Air Force]] established an airfield that served two airplanes,{{#tag:ref|The British did not occupy the area and the local Bedouins agreed to protect the field.<ref name="raf">{{cite book|url=https://books.google.nl/books?id=LG2cG5SshpEC&pg=PA228#v=onepage&q&f=false|title=The Battle for Syria, 1918-1920|author= John D. Grainger|page= 228|year= 2013}}</ref>|group=note}}<ref name="raf" /><ref>{{cite book|url=https://books.google.nl/books?id=ke3EOOUq3gwC&pg=PA235#v=onepage&q&f=false|title=Victory 1918|author= Alan Warwick Palmer|page= 235|year= 2000}}</ref> and in November 1918, the Ottomans retreated from Zor Sanjak without a fight.{{#tag:ref|Neither the British, French or Arab armies attacked the Sanjak.<ref name="rafas">{{cite book|url=https://books.google.nl/books?id=36ptAAAAMAAJ&q|title=Athawra al-Manseya|language= ar|author= Zubair Sultan Qadduri|page= 50|year= 2000}}</ref>|group=note}}<ref name="rafas" /> The [[Arab Kingdom of Syria#The Arab constitutional government|Syrian Emirate]]'s army entered [[Deir ez-Zor]] in 4 December 1918, and the Sanjak became part of Syria.<ref name="rafas2">{{cite book|url=https://books.google.nl/books?id=36ptAAAAMAAJ&q|title=Athawra al-Manseya|language= ar|author= Zubair Sultan Qadduri|page= 51|year= 2000}}</ref> Following the war In 1919, as the British and French argued over the borders of the planned [[League of Nations mandate|Mandates]],<ref name="raf" /> [[Sir Henry Wilson, 1st Baronet|Henry Wilson]], the British Permanent Military Representative at the [[Supreme War Council]], suggested adding Palmyra to the [[British Mandate for Mesopotamia (legal instrument)|British mandate]].<ref name="raf" /> However, British general [[Edmund Allenby, 1st Viscount Allenby|Allenby]] persuaded his government to abandon this plan,<ref name="raf" /> and Syria along with Palmyra became part of the [[French Mandate for Syria and the Lebanon|French Mandate]], following the Syrian defeat at the [[Battle of Maysalun]] in 24 July 1920.<ref>{{cite book|url=https://books.google.nl/books?id=1Z7TbtGaAX8C&pg=PA28#v=onepage&q&f=false|title=Occupying Syria Under the French Mandate: Insurgency, Space and State Formation|author=Daniel Neep|page= 28|year= 2012}}</ref>

As Palmyra gained importance in the French efforts to pacify the [[Syrian Desert]], a base was built in the village near the temple of Bel in 1921.<ref name="faho9876">{{cite book|url=https://books.google.nl/books?id=1Z7TbtGaAX8C&pg=PA142#v=onepage&q&f=false|title=Occupying Syria Under the French Mandate: Insurgency, Space and State Formation|author=Daniel Neep|page= 142|year= 2012}}</ref> In 1929, [[Henri Arnold Seyrig]], the general director of antiquities in Syria, started excavating the ruins and convinced the villagers to relocate into a newly French built village, adjacent to the ancient site.<ref name="faho98765">{{cite book|url=https://books.google.nl/books?id=jv2jHT_GRe0C&pg=PA257#v=onepage&q&f=false|title=Syria|author=Diana Darke|page= 257|year= 2010}}</ref> The relocation was completed in 1932,<ref name="archo5l">{{cite book|url=https://books.google.nl/books?id=8kLFfE1qPhIC&pg=PA12#v=onepage&q&f=false|title= Palmyra and Its Empire: Zenobia's Revolt Against Rome|author=Richard Stoneman|page= 12|year= 1994}}</ref> making the ancient Palmyra ready for excavations,<ref name="faho98765" /> while the villagers settled in the new village that retained the name [[Tadmur]].<ref>{{cite book|url=https://books.google.nl/books?id=muQ3AAAAIAAJ&pg=PA4#v=onepage&q&f=false|title=Iconography of Religions|author=H. T. Bakker|page= 4|year= 1987}}</ref>

==People, language and society==
[[File:PalmyraWoman.JPG|thumb|A funerary relief, representing a Palmyrene.]]
{{further|Palmyrene dialect|Palmyrene alphabet}}
At its height during the reign of Zenobia, Palmyra had more than 200,000 resident.<ref>{{cite book|url=https://books.google.nl/books?id=0IKiAgAAQBAJ&pg=PA5#v=onepage&q&f=false|title=Improbable Women: Five who Explored the Middle East|author= William W. Cotterman|page= 5|year= 2013}}</ref> The earliest known inhabitants of Palmyra were the [[Amorites]] from the early second millennium BC,<ref>{{cite book|url=https://books.google.nl/books?id=S_Jjwq206QoC&pg=PT26#v=onepage&q&f=false|title=Horticultural Reviews, Horticultural Reviews|author= Jules Janick|page= 26|year= 2012}}</ref> and by the end of that millennium, the [[Arameans]] were mentioned as the inhabitants of the area.<ref>{{cite book|url=https://books.google.nl/books?id=amlXOOaSuLMC&pg=PA17#v=onepage&q&f=false|title=The Oxford Guide to People & Places of the Bible|author= Bruce Manning Metzger,Michael D. Coogan,Michael David Coogan|page= 17|year= 2004}}</ref><ref>{{cite book|url=https://books.google.nl/books?id=0IKiAgAAQBAJ&pg=PA4#v=onepage&q&f=false|title=Improbable Women: Five who Explored the Middle East|author= William W. Cotterman|page= 4|year= 2013}}</ref> [[Arabs]] arrived in the city in the late first millennium BC; Zabdibel's soldiers who aided the Seleucids in the battle of Raphia (217 BC), were described as Arabs.<ref name="trev34" /> The newcomers were assimilated by the earlier inhabitants, spoke their language,<ref name="dirvas" /> and formed an important part of the aristocracy.<ref>{{cite book|url=https://books.google.nl/books?id=OHfse3YY6NAC&pg=PA29#v=onepage&q&f=false|title=The Arabic Language|author= C. H. M. Versteegh,Kees Versteegh|page= 29|year= 2001}}</ref><ref>{{cite book|url=https://books.google.nl/books?id=227GhaeKYl4C&pg=PA11#v=onepage&q&f=false|title=The Syro-Aramaic Reading of the Koran: A Contribution to the Decoding of the Language of the Koran|author= Christoph Luxenberg|page= 11|year= 2007}}</ref> The city also included a [[Jewish]] minority, inscriptions written in Palmyrene from the necropolis of [[Beit She'arim National Park|Beit She'arim]] in [[Lower Galilee]], confirms the burial of some Palmyrene Jews in it.<ref>{{cite book|url=https://books.google.nl/books?id=oZcr7SzzVYYC&pg=PA209#v=onepage&q&f=false|title=A Journey to Palmyra: Collected Essays to Remember Delbert R. Hillers|author= Delbert R. Hillers,Eleonora Cussini|page= 209|year= 2005}}</ref>

By the time of the Rashidun conquest in 634, the city was inhabited by Christian Arabs.<ref>{{cite book|url=https://books.google.nl/books?id=BEvEV9OVzacC&pg=PA438#v=onepage&q&f=false|title=Byzantium and the Arabs in the Sixth Century, Volume 1|author= Irfan Shahid|page= 438|year= 1995}}</ref><ref name="archo5lss">{{cite book|url=https://books.google.nl/books?id=BEvEV9OVzacC&pg=PA439#v=onepage&q&f=false|title=Byzantium and the Arabs in the Sixth Century, Volume 1|author= Irfan Shahid|page= 439|year= 1995}}</ref> In the twelfth century, [[Benjamin of Tudela]] recorded the existence of 2000 Jews in the city,<ref>{{cite book|url=https://books.google.nl/books?id=8kLFfE1qPhIC&pg=PA192#v=onepage&q&f=false|title=Palmyra and Its Empire: Zenobia's Revolt Against Rome|author= Richard Stoneman|page= 192|year= 1994}}</ref>  which after the invasion by Timur, remained a small Arab village,<ref>{{cite book|url=https://books.google.nl/books?id=xMBWAAAAcAAJ&pg=PA341#v=onepage&q&f=false|title=The Pictorial Bible, Being the Old and New Testaments, Volume 2|author= John Kitto|page= 341|year= 1837}}</ref> of thirty or forty families,<ref>{{cite book|url=https://books.google.nl/books?id=8Vm_AAAAQBAJ&pg=PA86#v=onepage&q&f=false|title=The Rhetoric of Numbers in Gibbon's History|author= F. P. Lock|page= 86|year= 2012}}</ref> until the relocation of the inhabitants in 1932.<ref name="archo5l" />
[[File:Palmyrenisch.jpg|thumb|left|Palmyrene alphabet inscription.]]
The pre 272 AD Palmyrenes spoke their own [[Palmyrene dialect|dialect]] of the [[Aramaic language]] and wrote using the [[Palmyrene alphabet]].<ref>{{cite book|url=https://books.google.nl/books?id=pZ53zpMQNLEC&pg=PA28#v=onepage&q&f=false|title=The Aramaic Language, Its Distribution and Subdivisions|author=Klaus Beyer|page= 28|year= 1986}}</ref><ref>{{cite book|url=https://books.google.nl/books?id=0_KnI588AnkC&pg=PA46#v=onepage&q&f=false|title=The Early Alphabet|author=  John F. Healey|page= 46|year= 1990}}</ref> [[Greek Language|Greek]] was used by the wealthier parts of the society for commercial and diplomatic reasons, while the use of [[Latin]] was minimal.<ref name="arab palm" /> Greek became the dominant language during the era of the Byzantine empire, then, after the Arab conquest, it was replaced by [[Arabic language|Arabic]],<ref name="stan" /> from which a Palmyrene dialect evolved.<ref name="hillersss54">{{cite book|url=https://books.google.nl/books?id=l03h94vqCQMC&pg=PA21#v=onepage&q&f=false|title=Structuralist Studies in Arabic Linguistics: Charles A. Ferguson's Papers, 1954-1994|author= Charles Albert Ferguson|page= 21|year= 1997}}</ref>

The society of pre 272 AD was the result of mixture between the different peoples that inhabited the city,<ref name="palm3" /><ref>{{cite book|url=https://books.google.nl/books?id=TccUAAAAIAAJ&pg=PR9#v=onepage&q&f=false|title=The Pantheon of Palmyra|author= Javier Teixidor|page= 9|year= 1979}}</ref> which is manifested in the Aramaic,{{#tag:ref|E.g. Gaddibol and Yedi'bel.<ref name="hillers54">{{cite book|url=https://books.google.nl/books?id=8kLFfE1qPhIC&pg=PA67#v=onepage&q&f=false|title=Palmyra and Its Empire: Zenobia's Revolt Against Rome|author= Richard Stoneman|page= 67|year= 1994}}</ref>|group=note}} Arabic,{{#tag:ref|E.g. Bene Ma'zin.<ref name="hillers54" />|group=note}} and Amorite names of the clans.{{#tag:ref|E.g. for Amorite: Zmr' and Kohen-Nadu.<ref name="hillers54" />|group=note}}<ref name="hillers54" /><ref>{{cite book|url=http://books.google.nl/books?id=oZcr7SzzVYYC&pg=PA195#v=onepage&q&f=false|title=A Journey to Palmyra: Collected Essays to Remember Delbert R. Hillers|author=  Delbert R. Hillers,Eleonora Cussini|page= 195|year= 2005}}</ref> Palmyra was a tribal community,<ref>{{cite book|url=https://books.google.nl/books?id=h5cMho6zFckC&pg=PA38#v=onepage&q&f=false|title=Roman Palmyra: Identity, Community, and State Formation|author= Andrew M. Smith II|page= 38|year= 2013}}</ref> however, the tribal character is not to be understood in a [[nomad]]ic sense, but as a social grouping for people who have a common patrilineal descent with no political role, hence a ''tribe'' in Palmyra was mostly an extended family instead of political organization.<ref name="lamsin">{{cite book|url=https://books.google.nl/books?id=_LfXg2r6FT0C&pg=PA24#v=onepage&q&f=false|title=The Palmyrenes of Dura-Europos: A Study of Religious Interaction in Roman Syria|author= Lucinda Dirven|page= 24|year= 1999}}</ref> In total, fourteen clans are attested,<ref name="lamsin" /> five of them were identified as tribes ([[Phyle|Phyle (<U+03C6><U+03C5><U+03BB><U+03AE>)]]),{{#tag:ref|The Bene Mita, Komare, Mattabol, Ma'zin and Claudia.<ref name="lamsin" />|group=note}} comprising several sub-clans.<ref name="lamsin" /> By the time of [[Nero]], Palmyra was split into four tribes residing in four quarters, each quarter was named after the tribe that resided in it, those were the Komare, the Mattabol and the Ma'zin,<ref name="lamsin3">{{cite book|url=https://books.google.nl/books?id=_LfXg2r6FT0C&pg=PA25#v=onepage&q&f=false|title=The Palmyrenes of Dura-Europos: A Study of Religious Interaction in Roman Syria|author= Lucinda Dirven|page= 25|year= 1999}}</ref> while the fourth tribe's name is unknown with certainty but most probably it was the Mita.<ref name="lamsin3" /><ref name="lamsin1654">{{cite book|url=https://books.google.nl/books?id=_LfXg2r6FT0C&pg=PA74#v=onepage&q&f=false|title= The Palmyrenes of Dura-Europos: A Study of Religious Interaction in Roman Syria|author= Lucinda Dirven|page= 74|year= 1999}}</ref> As the time passed, the four tribes became highly superficial and civic,{{#tag:ref|In general, a civic tribe (Phyle) is a collection of people chosen from the collective population and ascribed a deity as a tribal ancestor, then assigned a territory for them to reside in. The Phyles were united by their citizenship instead of origin.<ref>{{cite book|url=https://books.google.nl/books?id=Ex8HGWKViYQC&pg=PA60#v=onepage&q&f=false|title=The Greek Discovery of Politics|author= Christian Meier|page= 60|year= 1990}}</ref>|group=note}}<ref name="lamsin3" /> while the rest of the clans might have gathered under the name of the four tribes, for by the second century, any notion of a clan lost its importance and disappeared in the following third century.<ref name="lamsin3" /> Later periods saw Palmyra's decline and transformation into a small village numbering 6000 at the beginning of the 20th century, and although surround by Bedouins, the villagers managed to preserve their own dialect,<ref name="hillersss54" /> and maintain an urban life of a small settlement.<ref name="desto8s9sa" />

==Culture==
[[File:Istanbul - Museo archeol. - Colombario funebre da Palmira - Foto G. Dall'Orto 28-5-2006.jpg|thumb|Burial compartments.]]
Palmyra had a distinctive culture,<ref name="fergo1">{{cite book|url= https://books.google.nl/books?id=IA-YlZqHv90C&pg=PA246#v=onepage&q&f=false|title= The Roman Near East, 31 B.C.-A.D. 337|author= Fergus Millar |page= 246 |year= 1993 }}</ref> which was influenced by the [[Greco-Roman world#Greco-Roman Culture|Greco-Roman]] culture.<ref>{{cite book|url= https://books.google.nl/books?id=DQgmOZlsEWcC&pg=PA33#v=onepage&q&f=false |title= Between Rome and Persia: The Middle Euphrates, Mesopotamia and Palmyra Under Roman Control|author= Peter Edwell |page= 33 |year= 2007 }}</ref> However, beneath the foreign influence, a [[Culture of Syria|local Semitic]] tradition defined the culture of the city,{{#tag:ref|E.g. by the second century, Palmyrene goddess Al-l<U+0101>t was portrayed in the style of the Greek goddess [[Athena]], and named Athena-Al-l<U+0101>t. However, this assimilation of Al-l<U+0101>t to Athena did not extend beyond iconography.<ref>{{cite book|url= https://books.google.nl/books?id=TccUAAAAIAAJ&pg=PA62#v=onepage&q&f=false|title= The Pantheon of Palmyra|author= Javier Teixidor |page= 62|year= 1979}}</ref>|group=note}}<ref>{{cite book|url= https://books.google.nl/books?id=q8Z7AgAAQBAJ&pg=PA281#v=onepage&q&f=false|title= Ancient Syria: A Three Thousand Year History|author= Trevor Bryce |page= 281 |year= 2014 }}</ref> and according to [[Fergus Millar]], Palmyra's culture is the result of fusion between the local and Greco-Roman traditions.<ref>{{cite book|url= https://books.google.nl/books?id=mimRtU4vtDwC&pg=PA108#v=onepage&q&f=false|title=From Rome to Constantinople: Studies in Honour of Averil Cameron |author=  Hagit Amirav,R. B. ter Haar Romeny |page= 108 |year= 2007 }}</ref> In addition to the western influence, the culture of [[Culture of Iran|Persia]] manifested its influence in the Palmyrene upper classes fondness of hunting,<ref name="war1" /> and in the Palmyrene art, military tactics, dress and court ceremonials.<ref name="war1" /> Palmyra lacked the intellectual movement that characterized other eastern cities such as [[Edessa]] or Antioch, as it contained no large libraries or publishing facilities.<ref name="loloi">{{cite book|url= https://books.google.nl/books?id=73-JAgAAQBAJ&pg=PA79#v=onepage&q&f=false|title= Rome in the East: The Transformation of an Empire|author= Warwick Ball|page= 73|year= 2002}}</ref> Zenobia opened her court to academics, however, the only notable scholar attested at the Palmyrene court was [[Cassius Longinus (philosopher)|Cassius Longinus]].<ref name="loloi" />
[[File:HPIM3153.JPG|thumb|left|The interior of Elahbel tomb.]]
The city included a large [[Agora]].{{#tag:ref|In the Hellenistic tradition, The Agora was the center of athletic, artistic, spiritual and political life of the city.<ref>{{cite book|url= https://books.google.nl/books?id=74JI2UlcU8AC&pg=PA66#v=onepage&q&f=false|title= International Dictionary of Historic Places: Southern Europe|author= Trudy Ring,Robert M. Salkin,Sharon La Boda|page= 66|year= 1995}}</ref>|group=note}} However, unlike the Greek Agoras which served as a place for public gatherings and a square shared by the civic public buildings, Palmyra's Agora belonged to the eastern tradition, and was closer to a [[Caravanserai]] and a marketplace than to a hub of public life.<ref>{{cite book|url= https://books.google.nl/books?id=0VK6uPyhFLAC&pg=PA198#v=onepage&q&f=false|title= Urban Development and Regional Identity in the Eastern Roman Provinces, 50 BC-AD 250: Aphrodisias, Ephesos, Athens, Gerasa|author= Rubina Raja|page= 198|year= 2012}}</ref><ref>{{cite book|url= https://books.google.nl/books?id=73-JAgAAQBAJ&pg=PA296#v=onepage&q&f=false|title= Rome in the East: The Transformation of an Empire|author= Warwick Ball|page= 296 |year= 2002}}</ref> The Palmyrenes buried their dead in elaborate family mausoleums,<ref>{{cite book|url= https://books.google.nl/books?id=lDmEAgAAQBAJ&pg=PA168#v=onepage&q&f=false|title=The Roman World|author=  V. Chapot|page= 168|year= 2005}}</ref> that had its interior walls constructed to form rows of burial compartments, in which the deceased, laid at full length, were placed.<ref>{{cite book|url= https://books.google.nl/books?id=gBCHchG6qDAC&pg=PA106#v=onepage&q&f=false|title= Art of the Ancient Near East: A Resource for Educators|author= Metropolitan Museum of Art|page= 106|year= 2010}}</ref><ref name="far2">{{cite book|url= https://books.google.nl/books?id=CMaY0_y6gK0C&pg=PA115#v=onepage&q&f=false|title= The Year One: Art of the Ancient World East and West|author= Metropolitan Museum of Art (New York, N.Y.) |page= 115|year= 2000}}</ref> Reliefs that represented the person interred formed part of the walls' decoration and functioned as a headstone.<ref name="far2" /> Some of the tombs contained [[mummies]] in full dress and jewelry,<ref>{{cite book|url= https://books.google.nl/books?id=W9LPbwWslTUC&pg=PA167#v=onepage&q&f=false|title= Cleopatra's Wedding Present: Travels Through Syria|author= Robert Tewdwr Moss|page= 167|year= 2001}}</ref> and the embalming methods used were similar to the [[Ancient Egyptian burial customs#Mummification|methods]] used in [[Ancient Egypt|Egypt]].<ref>{{cite book|url= https://books.google.nl/books?id=QOYRAwAAQBAJ&pg=PA22#v=onepage&q&f=false|title= The ruins of Palmyra, otherwise Tedmor, in the desart|author=  Robert Wood|page= 22|year= 1753}}</ref>

===Art and architecture===
The Palmyrene art was related to the [[Hellenistic art]], but had its own distinctive style, local to the wider middle Euphrates region.<ref name="far562">{{cite book|url= https://books.google.nl/books?id=IA-YlZqHv90C&pg=PA329#v=onepage&q&f=false|title= The Roman Near East, 31 B.C.-A.D. 337|author= Fergus Millar|page= 329|year= 1993}}</ref> Palmyrene art is best represented by the iconography of the deities, and the human bust reliefs that sealed the openings of the burial compartments.<ref name="far562" /> It was characteristic for focusing on the clothing, the attention for details such as jewelry,<ref name="far562ss">{{cite book|url= https://books.google.nl/books?id=PJ_mBQAAQBAJ&pg=PA252#v=onepage&q&f=false|title= A History of Roman Art|author= Steven L. Tuck|page= 252|year= 2015}}</ref> and the frontal representation of the person it depicted.<ref name="far562" /> Those characters could be seen as a forerunner for the later [[Byzantine art]].<ref name="far562" />

Similar to its art, Palmyra's architecture was influenced by the Greco-Roman style,<ref>{{cite book|url= https://books.google.nl/books?id=8kLFfE1qPhIC&pg=PA54#v=onepage&q&f=false|title= Palmyra and Its Empire: Zenobia's Revolt Against Rome|author= Richard Stoneman|page= 54|year= 1994}}</ref> but preserved local elements, which are best represented in the [[Temple of Bel]].<ref name="belo698">{{cite book|url= https://books.google.nl/books?id=8kLFfE1qPhIC&pg=PA64#v=onepage&q&f=false|title= Palmyra and Its Empire: Zenobia's Revolt Against Rome|author= Richard Stoneman|page= 64|year= 1994}}</ref> Although inclosed by a massive wall flanked with traditional Roman columns,<ref name="belo698" /><ref>{{cite book|url= https://books.google.nl/books?id=h5lVDl8uqMQC&pg=PA90#v=onepage&q&f=false|title= Out of the Past of Greece & Rome|author= Michael Ivanovitch Rostovtzeff|page= 90|year= 1971}}</ref> Bel's sanctuary was mostly Semitic in its general plan.<ref name="belo698" /> Similar to the [[Second Temple]], Bel's sanctuary consisted of a large courtyard, with the deity's main shrine located non centrally against the entrance of the sanctuary,<ref name="belo698" /> in a plan that preserve elements found in the temples of [[Ebla]] and [[Ugarit]].<ref>{{cite book|url= https://books.google.nl/books?id=8kLFfE1qPhIC&pg=PA65#v=onepage&q&f=false|title= Palmyra and Its Empire: Zenobia's Revolt Against Rome|author= Richard Stoneman|page= 65|year= 1994}}</ref>

==Government==
[[File:Palmyra Julius Aurelius Zenobius inscription.jpg|thumb|Inscription naming the strategos ''Julius Aurelius Zenobius''.]]
From the beginning of its history until the first century AD, Palmyra was a petty [[sheikhdom]],<ref>{{cite book|url=https://books.google.nl/books?id=xB8mAQAAMAAJ&hl|title=Out of Arabia: Phoenicians, Arabs, and the Discovery of Europe|author= Warwick Ball|page= 56|year= 2010}}</ref> but by the first century BC, a concept of Palmyrene identity started to develop.<ref name="lamsin3s5">{{cite book|url=https://books.google.nl/books?id=h5cMho6zFckC&pg=PA125#v=onepage&q&f=false|title=Roman Palmyra: Identity, Community, and State Formation|author=  Andrew M. Smith II|page= 125|year= 2013}}</ref> In the first half of the first century, the city adopted the institutions of a Greek city ([[polis]]).<ref name="lamsin3s">{{cite book|url=https://books.google.nl/books?id=h5cMho6zFckC&pg=PA122#v=onepage&q&f=false|title=Roman Palmyra: Identity, Community, and State Formation|author=  Andrew M. Smith II|page= 122|year= 2013}}</ref> The concept of citizenship ([[Glossary_of_rhetorical_terms#Demos|demos]]) appears in an inscription dated to 10 AD, describing the Palmyrenes as a community.<ref name="lamsin3ssa">{{cite book|url=https://books.google.nl/books?id=h5cMho6zFckC&pg=PA126#v=onepage&q&f=false|title=Roman Palmyra: Identity, Community, and State Formation|author=  Andrew M. Smith II|page= 126|year= 2013}}</ref> In 74 AD, another inscription mentions the [[Boule (ancient Greece)|boule]] (senate) of the city.<ref name="lamsin3s" /> The Palmyrene council consisted out of approximately six hundred members,{{#tag:ref|The number is hypothetical.<ref name="larome">{{cite book|url=https://books.google.nl/books?id=h5cMho6zFckC&pg=PA127#v=onepage&q&f=false|title=Roman Palmyra: Identity, Community, and State Formation|author=  Andrew M. Smith II|page= 127|year= 2013}}</ref>|group=note}} hailing from the local elite, such as the elders or heads of the wealthy families or clans,<ref name="larome" /> who represented the four quarters of the city.<ref name="lamsin1654" /> The boule was headed by a president,<ref name="laromeas" /> and managed the civic responsibilities;<ref name="larome" /> supervised the public works (e.g. the construction of public buildings), approved the expenditures, managed the collection of taxes,<ref name="larome" /> and appointed two [[Eponymous archon|archons]] (lords) annually.<ref name="zabo">{{cite book|url=https://books.google.nl/books?id=wnTOBAAAQBAJ&pg=PA43#v=onepage&q&f=false|title=Empress Zenobia: Palmyra's Rebel Queen|author=Pat Southern|page= 43|year= 2008}}</ref><ref name="laromeas">{{cite book|url=https://books.google.nl/books?id=h5cMho6zFckC&pg=PA128#v=onepage&q&f=false|title=Roman Palmyra: Identity, Community, and State Formation|author=  Andrew M. Smith II|page= 128|year= 2013}}</ref> The military units of Palmyra were headed by the [[Strategos|strategoi]] (generals),<ref>{{cite book|url=https://books.google.nl/books?id=h5cMho6zFckC&pg=PA129#v=onepage&q&f=false|title=Roman Palmyra: Identity, Community, and State Formation|author=  Andrew M. Smith II|page= 129|year= 2013}}</ref> who were appointed by the boule.<ref name="strato">{{cite book|url=https://books.google.nl/books?id=E5yCAgAAQBAJ&pg=PA145#v=onepage&q&f=false|title=Rome's Eastern Trade: International Commerce and Imperial Policy 31 BC - AD 305|author= Gary K. Young|page= 145|year= 2003}}</ref>

With the elevation of Palmyra into a [[Colonia (Roman)|colonia]] (c. 213-216), the city incorporated Roman institutions to its system, but kept most of its Greek institutions.<ref name="zabosa">{{cite book|url=https://books.google.nl/books?id=h5cMho6zFckC&pg=PA130#v=onepage&q&f=false|title=Roman Palmyra: Identity, Community, and State Formation|author=  Andrew M. Smith II|page= 130|year= 2013}}</ref> The boule remained and the strategos title came to designate one of two annually elected [[Roman magistrate|magistrates]],<ref name="zabosa" /> who constituted the [[duumviri]] which managed the new colonial constitution,<ref name="zabosa" /> and replaced the archons.<ref name="zabo" /> The political scene in Palmyra changed with the rise of Odaenathus, who was attested as senator and exarch (chief) of Palmyra along with his son Hairan in 251.<ref name="adnos56" /> The exact meaning of Odaenathus' title, whether it indicated a military or a priestly position, is unknown.<ref name="adnos56" /> By 257, Odaenathus was referred to as [[consularis]], which might indicate that he became the [[legatus]] of the [[Phoenice (Roman province)|Syria Phoenice]] province.<ref name="adnos56" /> Starting in 258, Odaenathus extended his political influence taking advantage of the instability in the region, caused by the Sassanid aggressions,<ref name="adnos56" /> which culminated with the Battle of Edessa,<ref name="satno" /> Odaenathus' mobilization of troops, his war with the Persians, and his subsequent royal elevation that turned Palmyra into a kingdom.<ref name="satno" />

The royal authority maintained the council,<ref>{{cite book|url=https://books.google.nl/books?id=ttiIAgAAQBAJ&pg=PT96#v=onepage&q&f=false|title=Aurelian and the Third Century|author= Alaric Watson|page= 96|year= 2004}}</ref> most of the civic institutions,<ref name="adnos56" /> and allowed the magistrates to be elected until 264.<ref name="zabo" /> Provincial governors continued to be appointed by Rome during Odaenathus' reign, but Palmyrene officials were appointed in the provinces to represent the king.<ref>{{cite book|url=https://books.google.nl/books?id=wnTOBAAAQBAJ&pg=PA75#v=onepage&q&f=false|title=Empress Zenobia: Palmyra's Rebel Queen|author= Pat Southern|page= 75|year= 2008}}</ref> However, during the rebellion of Zenobia, the governors were appointed by the queen directly.<ref>{{cite book|url=https://books.google.nl/books?id=ecfiAAAAQBAJ&pg=PA115#v=onepage&q&f=false|title=Empress Zenobia: Palmyra's Rebel Queen|author= Pat Southern|page= 115|year= 2008}}</ref> Not all Palmyrenes accepted the dominance of the royal family, a man with a senatorial rank named ''Septimius Haddudan'', appears in one of the latest Palmyrene inscriptions as having aided the armies of Aurelian during the 273 rebellion.<ref>{{cite book|url=https://books.google.nl/books?id=YJPn3-rRjC0C&pg=PA60#v=onepage&q&f=false|title=Roman Syria and the Near East|author= Kevin Butcher|page= 60|year= 2003}}</ref><ref name="frontsaaaao">{{cite book|url=https://books.google.nl/books?id=kJ2JAgAAQBAJ&pg=PA81#v=onepage&q&f=false|title=Aurelian and the Third Century|author=Alaric Watson|page= 81|year= 2004}}</ref> Following the Roman destruction of the city, Palmyra lost its statehood and was ruled directly by the Romans,<ref>{{cite book|url=https://books.google.nl/books?id=W4H97SA6pMAC&pg=PA15#v=onepage&q&f=false|title=Rome and the Arabs: A Prolegomenon to the Study of Byzantium and the Arabs|author= Irfan Shah<U+00EE>d|page= 15|year= 1984}}</ref> and the following states (e.g. the Burids and Ayyubids),<ref name="umaj23" /><ref>{{cite book|url=https://books.google.nl/books?id=itI_AQAAIAAJ&q|title=Balsam al-sh<U+0101>f<U+012B> f<U+012B> t<U+0101>r<U+012B>kh Tadmur al-w<U+0101>f<U+012B>, dir<U+0101>sah wa-ta<U+2019>r<U+012B>kh|language= ar|author=  A<U+1E25>mad Mithq<U+0101>l Qash<U+2018>am Vol 3-4|page= 245|year= 2004}}</ref> or by subordinate Bedouin chiefs, mainly the Fadl family who ruled as governors for the Mamluks.<ref>{{cite book|url=https://books.google.nl/books?id=7y9IAAAAMAAJ&q|title=al-<U+1E24>ayat al-Ejtema'eya f<U+012B> Bilad al-Sham f<U+012B> al-'asrayen al-Ayubi wal Mamluki|language= ar|author= Ibrahim Za<U+00B4>rur|page= 106|year= 1993}}</ref>

===Palmyrene military===
The army was an important institution for Palmyra's protection and economy, it helped extend the Palmyrene authority beyond the city walls, and protected the countrysides, specially the desert trade routes.<ref>{{cite book|url=https://books.google.nl/books?id=h5cMho6zFckC&pg=PA143#v=onepage&q&f=false|title=Roman Palmyra: Identity, Community, and State Formation|author= Andrew M. Smith II|page= 143|year= 2013}}</ref> Palmyra was able to amass substantial forces,<ref name="trevo 40" /> in the 3rd century BC, Zabdibel commanded a force of 10000,<ref name="trev34" /> and in the [[Battle of Emesa]], Zenobia led an army of 70000 soldiers.<ref name="fronto89">{{cite book|url=https://books.google.nl/books?id=5Zy2vZVx2mQC&pg=PA50#v=onepage&q&f=false|title=Imperial Roman Legionary AD 161-284|author= Ross Cowan|page= 50|year= 2003}}</ref> Those forces were recruited mostly from the city inhabitants, and the inhabitants of the Palmyrene territories, that spanned several thousand square kilometers stretching from the outskirts of Homs to the Euphrates valley.<ref name="trevo 40" /> Palmyra also recruited non Palmyrene soldiers, a [[Nabatean]] cavalryman is recorded in 132 as serving in a Palmyrene unit stationed at [[Anah]].<ref name="fronto89" /> The recruiting system is unknown, it is possible that the city selected and equipped the troops, while the many military generals (strategoi) led, trained and disciplined them.<ref>{{cite book|url=https://books.google.nl/books?id=ecfiAAAAQBAJ&pg=PA26#v=onepage&q&f=false|title=Empress Zenobia: Palmyra's Rebel Queen|author= Pat Southern|page= 26|year= 2008}}</ref> The strategoi were appointed by the boule with the approval of Rome,<ref name="strato" /> while the royal army was under the leadership of the monarch and the generals,<ref>{{cite book|url=https://books.google.nl/books?id=g4ZmqsyC5kEC&pg=PA162#v=onepage&q&f=false|title=A Companion to the Roman Empire|author= David S. Potter|page= 162|year= 2009}}</ref><ref>{{cite book|url=https://books.google.nl/books?id=8kLFfE1qPhIC&pg=PA122#v=onepage&q&f=false|title=Palmyra and Its Empire: Zenobia's Revolt Against Rome|author= Richard Stoneman|page= 122|year= 1994}}</ref> and modeled on the [[Military of the Sasanian Empire|Sassanid style]] in regard to arms and tactics.<ref name="war1">{{cite book|url=https://books.google.nl/books?id=qQKIAgAAQBAJ&pg=PA86#v=onepage&q&f=false|title=Rome in the East: The Transformation of an Empire|author= Warwick Ball|page= 86|year= 2002}}</ref> The Palmyrenes were famed as archers,<ref>{{cite book|url=https://books.google.nl/books?id=muVoB0O_XXMC&pg=PT62#v=onepage&q&f=false|title=The Fall Of The West: The Death Of The Roman Superpower|author= Adrian Goldsworthy|page= 62|year= 2009}}</ref> they utilized infantry,<ref>{{cite book|url=https://books.google.nl/books?id=ecfiAAAAQBAJ&pg=PA24#v=onepage&q&f=false|title=Empress Zenobia: Palmyra's Rebel Queen|author= Pat Southern|page= 24|year= 2008}}</ref> and counted on the heavily armored cavalry ([[cataphract]]) as the main attack force.<ref>{{cite book|url=https://books.google.nl/books?id=0IU9fduDRIMC&pg=PA107#v=onepage&q&f=false|title=Why Europe?: The Medieval Origins of Its Special Path|author= Michael Mitterauer|page= 107|year= 2010}}</ref> Palmyrene infantry were armed with swords,<ref name="dadas" /> lances and small round shields, while the cataphract were fully armored including the horses, and used heavy spears ([[Kontos (weapon)|kontos]]) 3.65 centimeter in length without a shield.<ref>{{cite book|url=https://books.google.nl/books?id=SDxrLQymWWwC&pg=PA18#v=onepage&q&f=false|title=The Walls of Rome|author= Nic Fields|page= 18|year= 2008}}</ref>

====Relation with Rome====
Citing their combating skills in large and sparsely populated areas, the Romans formed Palmyrene [[auxilia]] to serve in the [[Imperial Roman army]].<ref name="dadas" /> Vaspasian reputedly had 8000 Palmyrene archers serving in [[Judea]],<ref name="dadas" /> and Trajan established the first official Palmyrene auxilia in 116 (the camel cavalry unit, Ala I Ulpia dromedariorum Palmyrenorum).<ref name="dadas" /><ref name="icaan54">{{cite book|url=https://books.google.nl/books?id=8kLFfE1qPhIC&pg=PA27#v=onepage&q&f=false|title= Palmyra and Its Empire: Zenobia's Revolt Against Rome|author= Richard Stoneman|page= 27|year= 1994}}</ref><ref>{{cite book|url=https://books.google.nl/books?id=1D612o_X2VYC&pg=PA258#v=onepage&q&f=false|title= A Companion to the Roman Army|author= Paul Erdkamp|page= 258|year= 2011}}</ref> Palmyrene units were deployed all around the Roman empire,{{#tag:ref|A Palmyrene monument was discovered near [[Newcastle upon Tyne|Newcastle]] in [[England]], it was set by a Palmyrene named ''Baratas'', who was either a soldier or a camp follower.<ref>{{cite book|url=https://books.google.nl/books?id=YkgTbON-GGUC&pg=PA80#v=onepage&q&f=false|title= The World of Rome: An Introduction to Roman Culture|author= Peter V. Jones,Keith C. Sidwell|page= 80|year= 1997}}</ref>|group=note}} late in Hadrian's reign, Palmyrenes were serving in [[Roman Dacia|Dacia]],<ref name="icaan5sa4">{{cite book|url=https://books.google.nl/books?id=DQgmOZlsEWcC&pg=PA137#v=onepage&q&f=false|title= Between Rome and Persia: The Middle Euphrates, Mesopotamia and Palmyra Under Roman Control|author= Peter Edwell|page= 137|year= 2007}}</ref> and during [[Antoninus Pius]]' reign, they served at [[El Kantara]] in [[Numidia]] and at [[Moesia]].<ref name="icaan5sa4" /><ref>{{cite book|url=https://books.google.nl/books?id=Ig0_4HeMh-AC&pg=PA878#v=onepage&q&f=false|title= Politische Geschichte (Provinzen und Randv<U+00F6>lker: Sizilien und Sardinien; Italien und Rom; Allgemeines)|author= Hildegard Temporini|page= 878|year= 1982}}</ref> Toward the end of the second century, Rome formed the [[Cohors XX Palmyrenorum]], which was stationed in [[Dura-Europus]].<ref name="icaan5sa4" />

