==Religion==
[[File:Relief Bel Baalshamin Yarhibol Aglibol MBA Lyon 1992-13.jpg|thumb|Right to left : Bel, Yarhibol, Aglibol and Baalshamin.]]
The Palmyrene deities belonged mostly to the [[Canaanite religion|Northwest Semitic]] pantheon, in addition to the [[Ancient Mesopotamian religion|Mesopotamian]] and [[Arabian mythology|Arab]] pantheons.<ref name="varga">{{cite book|url=https://books.google.nl/books?id=BjkfKsCttrkC&pg=PA15#v=onepage&q&f=false|title= Julia Domna: Syrian Empress|author= Barbara Levick|page= 15|year= 2007}}</ref> The city's pre-Hellenistic chief deity was [[Bol (Deity)|Bol]],<ref name="vargasaa">{{cite book|url=https://books.google.nl/books?id=TccUAAAAIAAJ&pg=PA1#v=onepage&q&f=false|title= The Pantheon of Palmyra|author=Javier Teixidor|page= 29|year= 1979}}</ref> whose name is an abbreviation of [[Baal]], the Northwest Semitic title for chief deity.<ref name="dsaae">{{cite book|url=https://books.google.nl/books?id=69YUAAAAIAAJ&pg=PA46#v=onepage&q&f=false|title=Cults and Beliefs at Edessa|author=  H. J. W. Drijvers|page= 46|year= 1980}}</ref> Due to the influence of the Babylonian cult of [[Marduk|Bel Marduk]],<ref name="vargasaa" /> Bol's name became [[Bel (mythology)|Bel]], however, the change did not indicate the replacing of Bol with a Mesopotamian deity, but was a mere change in the name.<ref name="dsaae" /> Placed second in importance after the supreme deity, were the ancestral gods of the different Palmyrene clans,<ref name="dsaaeas3">{{cite book|url=https://books.google.nl/books?id=rMmsS7tr1AEC&pg=PA33#v=onepage&q&f=false|title=Islam: Historical, Social, and Political Perspectives|author=Jean Jacques Waardenburg|page= 33|year= 2002}}</ref> and they included more than sixty deities.<ref>{{cite book|url=https://books.google.nl/books?id=n_InAAAAYAAJ&q|title=Strangers and sojourners: religious communities in the diaspora|author=Gerrie ter Haar|page= 83|year= 1998}}</ref> Palmyra had its unique deities;<ref name="varg456a">{{cite book|url=https://books.google.nl/books?id=YJPn3-rRjC0C&pg=PA345#v=onepage&q&f=false|title= Roman Syria and the Near East|author= Kevin Butcher|page= 345|year= 2003}}</ref> the justice god and Efqa's guardian [[Yarhibol]],<ref name="zorbo">{{cite book|url=https://books.google.nl/books?id=h5cMho6zFckC&pg=PA64#v=onepage&q&f=false|title=Roman Palmyra: Identity, Community, and State Formation|author= Andrew M. Smith II|page= 64|year= 2013}}</ref><ref>{{cite book|url=https://books.google.nl/books?id=h5cMho6zFckC&pg=PA66#v=onepage&q&f=false|title=Roman Palmyra: Identity, Community, and State Formation|author= Andrew M. Smith II|page= 66|year= 2013}}</ref> the sun god [[Malakbel]],<ref name="zorbossssss">{{cite book|url=https://books.google.nl/books?id=TccUAAAAIAAJ&pg=PA52#v=onepage&q&f=false|title=The Pantheon of Palmyra|author= Javier Teixidor|page= 52|year= 1979}}</ref> and the moon god [[Aglibol]].<ref name="zorbossssss" /> In addition, Palmyrenes worshiped regional deities; the wider Syrian [[Astarte]], [[Baal-hamon]], [[Baalshamin]] and [[Atargatis]],<ref name="varg456a" /> the Babylonian [[Nabu]] and [[Nergal]],<ref name="varg456a" /> and the Arab [[Azizos]], [[Arsu]], [[Shamash|<U+0160>ams]] and [[Al-l<U+0101>t]].<ref name="zorbo" /><ref name="varg456a" />
[[File:L-a80 2005-12-29 0050.jpg|thumb|left| Baalshamin (center), Aglibol (right) and Malakbel (left).]]
The Palmyrene pantheon included a group of lesser deities named the [[ginnaye]], that were prominent in the countrysides,<ref>{{cite book|url=https://books.google.nl/books?id=mQnv_Wh3gCwC&pg=PA273#v=onepage&q&f=false|title=Struggles of Gods: Papers of the Groningen Work Group for the Study of the History of Religions|author= Hans Gerhard Kippenberg, H. J. W. Drijvers|page= 273|year= 1984}}</ref> and had similarities with both the Arab [[jinn]] and the Roman [[Genius (mythology)|genius]].<ref name="dsssss">{{cite book|url=https://books.google.nl/books?id=TccUAAAAIAAJ&pg=PA77#v=onepage&q&f=false|title=The Pantheon of Palmyra|author= Javier Teixidor|page= 77|year= 1979}}</ref> ginnaye were believed to have the appearance and behavior of humans which is similar to the Arab jinn.<ref name="dsssss" /> However, the ginnaye unlike the jinn, did not [[Demonic possession|possess]] or hurt the humans,<ref name="dsssss" /> but had a role similar to the genius, they were [[Tutelary deity|Tutelary deities]] who guarded the people, their caravans, cattle and villages.<ref name="dsssss" /><ref name="dsaaeas3" />

The Palmyrenes worshiped each deity individually, but also associated some of them with other gods.<ref name="a26sa">{{cite book|url=https://books.google.nl/books?id=_LfXg2r6FT0C&pg=PA159#v=onepage&q&f=false|title= The Palmyrenes of Dura-Europos: A Study of Religious Interaction in Roman Syria|author= Lucinda Dirven|page= 159|year= 1999}}</ref> Bel had [[Astarte-Belti]] as his consort, and formed a triad with Aglibol and Yarhibol who became a sun god in his association with Bel.<ref name="zorbo" /><ref>{{cite book|url=https://books.google.nl/books?id=muQ3AAAAIAAJ&pg=PA12#v=onepage&q&f=false|title= Iconography of Religions|author= H. T. Bakker|page= 12|year= 1987}}</ref> Malakbel was present in many of the associations,<ref name="a26sa" /> he formed a pair with Aglibol,<ref name="varg45df6a">{{cite book|url=https://books.google.nl/books?id=_LfXg2r6FT0C&pg=PA160#v=onepage&q&f=false|title= The Palmyrenes of Dura-Europos: A Study of Religious Interaction in Roman Syria|author= Lucinda Dirven|page= 160|year= 1999}}</ref> a pair with [[Gad Taimi]],<ref name="varg45df6a" /> and a triad with Baalshamin and Aglibol.<ref name="savas2">{{cite book|url=https://books.google.nl/books?id=_LfXg2r6FT0C&pg=PA161#v=onepage&q&f=false|title= The Palmyrenes of Dura-Europos: A Study of Religious Interaction in Roman Syria|author= Lucinda Dirven|page= 161|year= 1999}}</ref> Palmyra held the [[Akitu]] (spring) festival every [[Nisan]].<ref>{{cite book|url=https://books.google.nl/books?id=SV_BUjJAabUC&pg=PA37#v=onepage&q&f=false|title=The Ak<U+012B>tu Festival: Religious Continuity and Royal Legitimation in Mesopotamia|author= Julye Bidmead|page= 37|year= 2004}}</ref> Each of the four quarters of the city included a sanctuary for a deity that is considered ancestral to the tribe that resided in it, the pair Malakbel and Aglibol had their sanctuary in the Komare's quarter.<ref name="savas">{{cite book|url=https://books.google.nl/books?id=TccUAAAAIAAJ&pg=PA36#v=onepage&q&f=false|title= The Pantheon of Palmyra|author= Javier Teixidor|page= 36|year= 1979}}</ref> Baalshamin sanctuary was located in the he Ma'zin's quarter, Arsu in the Mattabol's quarter,<ref name="savas" /> and Atargatis in the fourth tribe's quarter.{{#tag:ref|The fourth tribe's name is not certain but most likely the Mita.<ref name="savas2" />|group=note}}<ref name="savas2" />

With the spreading of Christianity across the Roman empire, Palmyra's pagan religion was replaced and a bishop is attested in the city by 325.<ref name="desto89" /> Most of the temples were turned into churches, while the temple of Al-l<U+0101>t was destroyed in 385, by the orders of [[Maternus Cynegius]], the [[Praetorian prefect of the East]].<ref name="desto89" /> Following the Arab conquest in 634, [[Islam]] gradually replaced Christianity and the last attested bishop of Palmyra was consecrated in 818.<ref name="archo5lss" />

==Economy==
[[File:Agora -1 Palmyra Syria.JPG|thumb|The Tariff Court.]]
Palmyra's economy before and at the beginning of the Roman period was based on agriculture, pastoralism, minor trade,<ref name="pliny" /> and acting as a rest station for caravans that sporadically crossed the desert road.<ref name="warwik" /> By the end of the first century BC, Palmyra had a mixed economy based on agriculture, pastoralism,<ref name="agros">{{cite book|url=https://books.google.nl/books?id=h5cMho6zFckC&pg=PA51#v=onepage&q&f=false|title= Roman Palmyra: Identity, Community, and State Formation|author= Andrew M. Smith II|page= 51|year= 2013}}</ref> taxation,<ref name="lutfan2sa">{{cite book|url=https://books.google.nl/books?id=8kLFfE1qPhIC&pg=PA57#v=onepage&q&f=false|title= Palmyra and Its Empire: Zenobia's Revolt Against Rome|author= Richard Stoneman|page= 57|year= 1994}}</ref> and most importantly, caravan trade.<ref name="lutfan">{{cite book|url=https://books.google.nl/books?id=6QPWXrCCzBIC&pg=PA158#v=onepage&q&f=false|title= Transnationalism in Ancient and Medieval Societies: The Role of Cross-Border Trade and Travel|author= Michael C. Howard|page= 158|year= 2012}}</ref>

Taxation provided an important source of income for the city.<ref name="lutfan2sa" /> Caravaneers paid the taxes in a building named the [[Tariff Court]],<ref name="tarov">{{cite book|url=https://books.google.nl/books?id=q8Z7AgAAQBAJ&pg=PA282#v=onepage&q&f=false|title= Ancient Syria: A Three Thousand Year History|author= Trevor Bryce|page= 282|year= 2014}}</ref> where the Palmyrene tax law dated to 137 was discovered.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.jstor.org/discover/10.2307/299013?sid=21105219327371&uid=70&uid=2&uid=4&uid=2134&uid=3738736|title= J. F. Matthews, The Tax Law of Palmyra: Evidence for Economic History in a City of the Roman East, The Journal of Roman Studies Vol. 74, (1984), pp. 157-180|publisher= Society for the Promotion of Roman Studies|date=1984|accessdate=31 January 2015}}</ref> The law regulated the different tariffs that the merchants had to pay in regard to the articles meant for the internal market.<ref name="tarov" /> Most of the lands were possessed by the city, which collected grazing taxes on its lands.<ref name="agros" /> The oasis had approximately 1000 hectares of irrigable land,<ref>{{cite book|url=https://books.google.nl/books?id=iwxeHaKUGFMC&pg=PA130#v=onepage&q&f=false|title=The Transformation of Nomadic Society in the Arab East|author=  Martha Mundy,Basim Musallam|page= 130|year= 2000}}</ref> in addition to the lands of the countrysides. However, the agriculture was not enough to support the population and food had to be imported.<ref>{{cite book|url=https://books.google.nl/books?id=ecfiAAAAQBAJ&pg=PA27#v=onepage&q&f=false|title=Empress Zenobia: Palmyra's Rebel Queen|author= Pat Southern|page= 27|year= 2008}}</ref>

Following the destruction of 273, Palmyra became a market for villagers and nomads from the surrounding areas,<ref name="desto">{{cite book|url=https://books.google.nl/books?id=8kLFfE1qPhIC&pg=PA189#v=onepage&q&f=false|title= Palmyra and Its Empire: Zenobia's Revolt Against Rome|author= Richard Stoneman|page= 189|year= 1994}}</ref> and the city regained some of its old prosperity during the Ummayad era, evident by the discovering of a big Ummayad [[Souq]] located in the colonnade street.<ref>{{cite book|url=https://books.google.nl/books?id=XdFqgSBTYeYC&pg=PA54-IA30#v=onepage&q&f=false|title= The Byzantine and Early Islamic Near East|author= Hugh N. Kennedy|page= 54|year= 2006}}</ref> Palmyra continued as a minor trading center,<ref name="khalosa" /> until the Timurid destruction,<ref name="khalosaas" /> which reduced it into a settlement on the borders of the desert, with the inhabitants living off herding and cultivating a small area to acquire vegetables and corn.<ref>{{cite book|url=https://books.google.nl/books?id=2Zy3NgMGcu0C&pg=PA333#v=onepage&q&f=false|title= Damascus and Palmyra: a journey to the East, Volume 1|author=  Charles Greenstreet Addison|page= 333|year= 1838}}</ref>

===Palmyrene caravan trade===
[[File:Palmyra trade.png|thumb|The silk road.]]
The main trade route started in Palmyra and headed east to the Euphrates, where it connected to the [[Silk Road]].<ref>{{cite book|url=https://books.google.nl/books?id=08KbBQAAQBAJ&pg=PA145#v=onepage&q&f=false|title=Flora of the Silk Road: The Complete Illustrated Guide|author= Basak Gardner & Chris Gardner|page= 145|year= 2014}}</ref> Then the route descended south along the river toward the port of [[Charax Spasinu]] on the [[Persian Gulf]], where Palmyrene ships made the journey to [[India]] and back.<ref name="grba">{{cite book|url=https://books.google.nl/books?id=E5yCAgAAQBAJ&pg=PA133#v=onepage&q&f=false|title= Rome's Eastern Trade: International Commerce and Imperial Policy 31 BC - AD 305|author=  Gary K. Young|page= 133|year= 2003}}</ref> The merchandise were imported from India, [[China]] and [[Transoxiana]],<ref name="asadfaaaaaq">{{cite book|url=https://books.google.nl/books?id=Xno9AgAAQBAJ&pg=PA283#v=onepage&q&f=false|title= Ancient Syria: A Three Thousand Year History|author= Trevor Bryce|page= 283|year= 2014}}</ref> then exported west to Emesa or Antioch, and afterward to the [[Mediterranean Sea|Mediterranean]] ports,<ref>{{cite book|url=https://books.google.nl/books?id=8kLFfE1qPhIC&pg=PA19#v=onepage&q&f=false|title= Palmyra and Its Empire: Zenobia's Revolt Against Rome|author= Richard Stoneman|page= 19|year= 1994}}</ref> where they were transported to the different regions of the Roman empire.<ref name="grba" /> In addition to the traditional route, some Palmyrene merchants used the [[Red Sea#Ancient era|Red Sea route]],<ref name="asadfaaaaaq" /> probably as a result of the insecurities caused by the Parthian-Roman wars.<ref name="ejo">{{cite book|url=https://books.google.nl/books?id=DqMrR29Cc7MC&pg=PA111#v=onepage&q&f=false|title=Empress Zenobia: Palmyra s Rebel Queen|author= Pat Southern|page= 111|year= 2008}}</ref> The merchandise would be carried from the Sea ports by land to one of the [[Nile]] ports, and then taken to the Egyptian Mediterranean ports to be exported.<ref name="ejo" /> Inscriptions that attests the Palmyrene existence in Egypt goes back as early as Hadrian's reign.<ref>{{cite book|url=https://books.google.nl/books?id=ZDh2KKSlQg4C&pg=PA34#v=onepage&q&f=false|title=Arab Seafaring in the Indian Ocean in Ancient and Early Medieval Times|author= George Fadlo Hourani|page= 34|year= 1995}}</ref>

As Palmyra was not situated on the traditional Silk Road, which followed the Euphrates,<ref name="pliny" /> the Palmyrenes secured the desert route that passed their city and connected it to the Euphrates valley, and provided it with watering and sheltering points.<ref name="pliny" /> The Palmyrene route was used almost exclusively by Palmyrene merchants,<ref name="pliny" /> who expanded and maintained a presence in many cities, including [[Dura-Europos]] in 33 BC,<ref name="elrood" /> [[Babylon]] (by 19 AD), [[Seleucia]] (by 24 AD),<ref name="palmoi" /> and afterward in [[Dendera]], [[Qift|Coptos]],<ref>{{cite book|url=https://books.google.nl/books?id=AdqAAgAAQBAJ&pg=PT137#v=onepage&q&f=false|title= Rome's Eastern Trade: International Commerce and Imperial Policy 31 BC - AD 305|author=  Gary K. Young|page= 137|year= 2003}}</ref> [[Bahrain]], the [[Indus River Delta]], [[Merv]] and [[Rome]] among others.<ref name="asadfq">{{cite book|url=https://books.google.nl/books?id=73-JAgAAQBAJ&pg=PA76#v=onepage&q&f=false|title=Rome in the East: The Transformation of an Empire|author= Warwick Ball|page= 76|year= 2002}}</ref>

The caravan trade counted on patrons and merchants, the patrons were the owners of the lands on which the animals for the caravans were raised, and they provided the animals and guards for the merchants.<ref name="lutfan2">{{cite book|url=https://books.google.nl/books?id=6QPWXrCCzBIC&pg=PA159#v=onepage&q&f=false|title= Transnationalism in Ancient and Medieval Societies: The Role of Cross-Border Trade and Travel|author= Michael C. Howard|page= 159|year= 2012}}</ref> The merchants used the service of the patrons to conduct their business, however, the role of a merchant and a patron often overlapped, as the patron himself would sometimes lead the caravans.<ref name="lutfan2" /> The trade turned the city into one of the richest in the region,<ref name="lutfan" /> and made the Palmyrene merchants extremely wealthy, some caravans were financed by a single merchant,<ref name="tarov" /> such as ''Male' Agrippa'' who paid the entire cost of emperor Hadrian's visit in 129, and financed the rebuilding of Bel's temple in 139.<ref name="trev44" /> The main income generating article of trade was silk, which was brought from the east and exported to the west.<ref>{{cite book|url=https://books.google.nl/books?id=8kLFfE1qPhIC&pg=PA59#v=onepage&q&f=false|title= Palmyra and Its Empire: Zenobia's Revolt Against Rome|author= Richard Stoneman|page= 59|year= 1994}}</ref> Other goods transited and exported includes jade, muslin, spices, ebony, ivory and precious stones.<ref name="asadfq" /> For its internal markets,<ref name="lutfan2sa" /> Palmyra imported slaves, prostitutes, olive oil, dyed goods, myrrh and perfumes.<ref name="lutfan2sa" /><ref name="asadfq" />

==Scheme and excavation==
{{Multiple image|align=left|direction=vertical|image1=Tower tombs, Palmyra.jpg|image2=Three Brother's hypogeum, Palmyra.jpg|caption1=Valley of Tombs.|caption2=Underground tomb.}}
[[File:Palmyra's landmarks.png|thumb|Palmyra's landmarks.]]
Palmyra started as a small settlement near the Efqa spring on the southern bank of Wadi al-Qubur.<ref>{{cite book|url=https://books.google.nl/books?id=b9-KAgAAQBAJ&pg=PA204#v=onepage&q&f=false|title= From Mycenae to Constantinople: The Evolution of the Ancient City|author= Richard A. Tomlinson|page= 204|year= 2002}}</ref> This settlement is named the Hellenistic settlement, and it contained residence quarters that expanded to the northern bank of the Wadi in the first century.<ref name="icaan4" /> The walls of the city enclosed an extensive area on both banks of the wadi, while the walls rebuilt during Diocletian's era surrounded only the northern bank's sections.<ref name="icaan4" />

Most of the city's monumental projects were built on the northern bank of the wadi.<ref>{{cite book|url=https://books.google.nl/books?id=FgML1EdUiWUC&pg=PA230#v=onepage&q&f=false|title= Proceedings of the 4th International Congress of the Archaeology of the Ancient Near East, 29 March - 3 April 2004, Freie Universit<U+00E4>t Berlin: The reconstruction of environment : natural resources and human interrelations through time ; art history : visual communication|author= Hartmut K<U+00FC>hne, Rainer Maria Czichon, Florian Janoscha Kreppner|page= 230|year= 2008}}</ref> The temple of Bel is also located on the northern bank, on a [[tell]] which was the site of an earlier temple named the Hellenistic temple.<ref name="trev34s" /> However, excavations support the theory that the temple was originally located on the southern bank, and that the wadi's bed was diverted, in order to incorporate Bel's temple into the new urban organization of the city, which started with the prosperity of the late first century and early second century.<ref name="trev34sssssss" />

Also located north of the wadi, was the [[Great Colonnade at Palmyra|Great Colonnade]], Palmyra's {{convert|1.1|km|abbr=on}} long main street,<ref name="salk69">{{cite book|url=https://books.google.nl/books?id=gGMc04ge4yoC&pg=PA123#v=onepage&q&f=false|title= The Byzantine Shops at Sardis|author= J. Stephens Crawford|page= 123|year= 1990}}</ref> that extended from Bel's temple in the east,<ref>{{cite book|url=https://books.google.nl/books?id=0TsSdzpN39MC&pg=PA288#v=onepage&q&f=false|title= "Imitation Greeks": Being Syrian in the Greco-Roman World (175 BCE--275 CE).|author= Nathanael John Andrade|page= 288|year= 2009}}</ref> to the [[Funerary temple (Palmyra)|Funerary temple]] in the western end of the city.<ref>{{cite book|url=https://books.google.nl/books?id=qQKIAgAAQBAJ&pg=PA364#v=onepage&q&f=false|title= Rome in the East: The Transformation of an Empire|author= Warwick Ball|page= 364|year= 2002}}</ref> It has a monumental arch in its eastern section,<ref>{{cite book|url=https://books.google.nl/books?id=LwAcAQAAIAAJ&pg=PA239#v=onepage&q&f=false|title= The Quarterly Christian Spectator. Vol.9|author= Association of Yale faculty members|page= 239|year= 1837}}</ref> and in the middle of it stands a [[Tetrapylon]].<ref name="esth" />

On the left side of the colonnade, the so called Diocletian baths were located,<ref>{{cite book|url=https://books.google.nl/books?id=8kLFfE1qPhIC&pg=PA124#v=onepage&q&f=false|title= Palmyra and Its Empire: Zenobia's Revolt Against Rome|author=Richard Stoneman|page= 124|year= 1994}}</ref> and they were built on the ruins of an earlier building which might have served as the royal palace.<ref name="hillers54" /> Also built on the left side of the colonnade were the temple of Baalshamin,<ref>{{cite book|url=https://books.google.nl/books?id=h5cMho6zFckC&pg=PA22#v=onepage&q&f=false|title= Roman Palmyra: Identity, Community, and State Formation|author= Andrew M. Smith II|page= 22|year= 2013}}</ref> residential quarters,<ref>{{cite book|url=https://books.google.nl/books?id=muQ3AAAAIAAJ&pg=PA5#v=onepage&q&f=false|title= Iconography of Religions|author= H. T. Bakker|page= 5|year= 1987}}</ref> and the Byzantine churches which includes a 1,500-year-old church, the fourth in the city and believed to be the largest ever discovered in Syria.<ref name="chus" /> The church columns were estimated to be 6&nbsp;meters tall, and the base measured 12&nbsp;meters by 24&nbsp;meters.<ref name="chus" /> A small [[Amphitheatre]] was found in the church's courtyard.<ref name="chus" />

On the southern side of the colonnade, the temple of [[Nabu]] and the [[Roman Theatre at Palmyra|Roman theater]] were built.<ref>{{cite book|url=https://books.google.nl/books?id=_R-I_Gx5OgQC&pg=PA208#v=onepage&q&f=false|title= Syria & Lebanon. Ediz. Inglese|author=  Terry Carter,Lara Dunston,Amelia Thomas|page= 208|year= 2008}}</ref> Behind the theater were located a small senate building and the large Agora, with remains of a banquet room ([[Triclinium]]) and the Tariff Court.<ref>{{cite book|url=https://books.google.nl/books?id=HuXAHGDSjNIC&pg=PA240#v=onepage&q&f=false|title= Syria|author= Diana Darke|page= 240|year= 2006}}</ref> A transverse colonnade street at the western end of the colonnade leads to [[Camp of Diocletian|Diocletian's Camp]],<ref name="salk69" /><ref name="tarsv">{{cite book|url=https://books.google.nl/books?id=jHHhAAAAMAAJ&dq|title=The Roman and Byzantine army in the East: proceedings of a colloqium [sic] held at the Jagiellonian University, Krak<U+00F3>w in September 1992|author= Uniwersytet Jagiello<U+0144>ski. Instytut Historii|page= 11|year= 1994}}</ref> which was built by the Roman governor of Syria, [[Sosianus Hierocles]].<ref>{{cite book|url=https://books.google.nl/books?id=z_IBAwAAQBAJ&pg=PA216#v=onepage&q&f=false|title= Monuments of Syria: A Guide|author=Ross Burns|page= 216|year= 2009}}</ref> Nearby are the temple of [[Al-l<U+0101>t]] (2nd century AD) and the Damascus Gate.<ref>{{cite book|url=https://books.google.nl/books?id=DccmAQAAMAAJ&q|title= Palmyra|author=Iain Browning|page= 180|year= 1979}}</ref>

Outside the ancient walls, to the west, the Palmyrenes constructed a series of large-scale funerary monuments which now form the so-called Valley of Tombs,<ref>{{cite book|url=https://books.google.nl/books?id=z_IBAwAAQBAJ&pg=PA218#v=onepage&q&f=false|title= Monuments of Syria: A Guide|author= Ross Burns|page= 218|year= 2009}}</ref> a {{convert|1|km|abbr=on}} long [[necropolis]].<ref>{{cite book|url=https://books.google.nl/books?id=9iCfkTe8v2EC&pg=RA2-PA291#v=onepage&q&f=false|title= The Rough Guide to Syria|author= Andrew Beattie,Timothy Pepper|page= 291|year= 2001}}</ref> The monuments numbered more than 50 and were mostly in the shape of towers reaching up to four levels.<ref>{{cite book|url=https://books.google.nl/books?id=w8NPAAAAMAAJ&q|title= City and Sanctuary: Religion and Architecture in the Roman Near East|author=Peter Richardson|page= 47|year= 2002}}</ref> The city included other cemeteries in the north, southwest and southeast, where the tombs are mostly in the shape of a [[Hypogeum]] (underground tombs).<ref>{{cite book|url=https://books.google.nl/books?id=z_IBAwAAQBAJ&pg=PA219#v=onepage&q&f=false|title= Monuments of Syria: A Guide|author= Ross Burns|page= 219|year= 2009}}</ref><ref>{{cite book|url=https://books.google.nl/books?id=z_IBAwAAQBAJ&pg=PA220#v=onepage&q&f=false|title= Monuments of Syria: A Guide|author= Ross Burns|page= 220|year= 2009}}</ref>

===Excavations===
[[File:Tetrapylon Palmyra.jpg|thumb|The Tetrapylon.]]
During the [[Middle Ages]], the city was largely forgotten in the [[Western world|West]].<ref name="babseeasad" /> It was sporadically visited by travelers such as [[Pietro Della Valle]] (between 1616-1625), [[Jean-Baptiste Tavernier]] (in 1638), in addition to many [[Swedes|Swedish]] and [[Germans|German]] explorers.<ref name="archol">{{cite book|url=https://books.google.nl/books?id=8kLFfE1qPhIC&pg=PA7#v=onepage&q&f=false|title= Palmyra and Its Empire: Zenobia's Revolt Against Rome|author=Richard Stoneman|page= 7|year= 1994}}</ref> In 1678, a group of [[English people|English]] merchants visited the city, while the first scholarly description of it appeared in a book by [[Abednego Seller]] (1705).<ref name="archol" /> In 1751, an expedition led by [[Robert Wood (antiquarian)|Robert Wood]] and [[James Dawkins (antiquarian)|James Dawkins]] studied the architecture of the city,<ref name="archol" /> and visits by different travelers and antiquarians continued, including one by [[Lady Hester Stanhope]] in 1813.<ref name="archol" />

The first excavations were conducted in 1902 by [[Otto Puchstein]], followed in 1917 by [[Theodor Wiegand]].<ref name="archo5l" /> In 1929, the French general director of antiquities of Syria and Lebanon [[Henri Arnold Seyrig]], started a wide scale excavation in the site,<ref name="archo5l" /> which was halted by the [[WW2]], but resumed soon after its end.<ref name="archo5l" /> Between 1954 and 1956, the temple of Baalshamin was excavated by a Swiss expedition organized by the [[UNESCO]].<ref name="archo5l" /> Since 1958, the site was excavated by the [[Syrian Directorate-General of Antiquities]],<ref name="faho98765" /> in addition to Polish expeditions led by [[Kazimierz Micha<U+0142>owski]] (until 1980) and [[Michael Gawlikowski]] (until 1984).<ref name="archo5l" />

In November 2010, [[Austrians|Austrian]] media manager Helmut Thoma admitted to looting a Palmyrene grave in 1980, where he had stolen architectural pieces, today presented in his private living room.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.welt.de/fernsehen/article10768775/Es-war-Nacht-und-da-waren-Schlangen.html?wtmc=plista||title= Ex-RTL-Chef Thoma "Es war Nacht, und da waren Schlangen ..."|language= de|publisher= Die Wilt |date= 6 November 2010 |accessdate= 8 February 2015}}</ref> German and Austrian archaeologists protested against this crime.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.spektrum.de/news/ein-schlag-ins-gesicht/1054329|title= Ein Schlag ins Gesicht|language= de|publisher= Spektrum der Wissenschaft |date= 15 November 2010 |accessdate= 8 February 2015}}</ref>

===Current situation===
As a result of the [[Syrian Civil War]], the site was subjected to wide scale looting and damaged by the clashes between the combatants.<ref name="looting269">{{cite web |url=http://www.reuters.com/article/2013/04/03/us-syria-crisis-palmyra-idUSBRE9320HL20130403 |title= Syria's ancient oasis city of Palmyra threatened in fighting |publisher= Reuters |date=3 April 2013 |accessdate=8 February 2015}}</ref> In the summer of 2012, there was an increasing concern of looting of the museum and the site, when an amateur video was posted, showing Syrian soldiers carrying funerary stones.<ref name="looting88">{{cite web |url=http://observers.france24.com/fr/content/20120730-video-hommes-uniforme-pieces-archeologiques-craintes-pillage-palmyre-syrie-soldat-patrimoine|title= Une vid<U+00E9>o amateur ravive les craintes de pillage sur les sites arch<U+00E9>ologiques de Syrie|language= fr|publisher= France 24|date= 30 July 2012 |accessdate= 8 February 2015}}</ref> However, according to [[France 24]]'s report; "from the information gathered, it is impossible to determine whether pillaging was taking place."<ref name=looting88/> In 2013, Bel's temple facade had a large circle caused by a mortar bomb, and the columns of colonnade have been damaged by [[Fragmentation (weaponry)|shrapnel]].<ref name=looting269/> According to Maamoun Abdulkarim, the director of antiquities and museums at the [[Ministry of Culture (Syria)|Syrian Ministry of Culture]], the [[Syrian Army]] positioned its troops in some of the archaeological site's areas,<ref name=looting269/> while the [[Syrian opposition]] soldiers are stationed in the gardens around the city.<ref name=looting269/>

In May 2015, it was reported that militants from the [[Islamic State of Iraq and the Levant]] were advancing on the site, raising fears that it would be destroyed in the same style of [[Nimrud]].<ref name=Tharoor>{{cite news|last1=Tharoor|first1=Ishaan|title=Islamic State fighters are at the gates of an ancient Roman-era city in Syria|url=http://www.washingtonpost.com/blogs/worldviews/wp/2015/05/14/islamic-state-fighters-are-at-the-gates-of-an-ancient-roman-era-city-in-syria/?postshare=3891431640485318|accessdate=14 May 2015|publisher=[[Washington Post]]|date=14 May 2015}}</ref>

